<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Party Politburo Calls for Efforts to Eliminate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The top administrative organ of
the Communist Party of Vietnam (CPV) has called for stepping up
efforts to eliminate hunger and alleviate poverty.
</P>
<P>
The appeal, by the Politburo of the CPV Central Committee, was
made in a recent instruction to party and government
organizations, and carried Wednesday by official media here.
</P>
<P>
Greater efforts are needed to bring down the country's
percantage of poor and hungry households from 20-25 percent
currently to 10 percent by year 2000, the instruction said.
</P>
<P>
To reach the goal, set last year by the CPV's Eighth National
Congress, party organizations should focus on some key issues,
such as proper land use and better use of local resources, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Politburo also called for the gradual implementation of the
policy to cut all or part of school fees for children from
poverty-stricken families, and of medical charges for poor people.
</P>
<P>
There are nearly 2.9 million households classified as "poor"
throughout Vietnam, including 600,000 households in rural areas
where people often don't have enough food, the party document said.
</P>
<P>
These households in poverty account for 19.3 percent of the
country's total, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
