<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Parliament Adopts Law on More Foreign Borrowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, Wednesday adopted in the first reading a
draft law allowing the government to increase the 1997 foreign
borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, foreign borrowing is to be increased from 45.9
trillion rubles (8.4 billion U.S. dollars) to 52.45 trillion
rubles (8.86 billion dollars), the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The law sets the upper limit of the 1997 foreign borrowing at
10.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
This draft law is aimed at reducing the soaring cost of
borrowing on domestic and foreign markets, said a statement
released by the budget committee.
</P>
<P>
It also said that yields on government securities tend to
increase and exceed the yields on borrowings on external financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
This law will help preserve the volume of borrowings stipulated
in the federal law on the 1997 federal budget and will increase
the efficiency of loans by restructuring them, the statement
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
