<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Launches Debate on Improvement of Ports Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, Wednesday called for a
Europe-wide debate on how to improve the efficiency of ports and
their integration into the EU's transport network.
</P>
<P>
The Commission Wednesday invited EU institutions, port
authorities, operators and the maritime industries to take up the
debate.
</P>
<P>
Ports had tended to remain on the sidelines of the general
transport debate on the EU's transport policy.
</P>
<P>
A green paper published Wednesday sets out possible
improvements in existing policies and identifies other areas,
particularly in the field of charging and market access where new
initiatives might be taken.
</P>
<P>
The commission also proposed to integrate better ports and
other interconnection points into the guidelines which detail the
exact makeup of the Trans-European Transport Network (TENs).
</P>
<P>
The proposal to adapt the TENs transport guidelines will, if
endorsed by EU member states and the European Parliament, include
300 European ports as part of the TENs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
