<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Again Express Reservation Over 35-Hour Work Week Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
on Wednesday again expressed his reservation over the draft law on
35-hour work week presented by the Socialist government.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think in fact that the draft law, taking into account
its obligatory and constraining character, would be favorable to
jobs," Chirac told a cabinet session.
</P>
<P>
However, all cabinet members expressed approval of the law
prepared by the Minister of Employment and Solidarity, Martine
Aubry, as a job-creating measure.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time that Chirac expressed his opposition to
the law.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said the solution to the country's 12.5 percent jobless
rate lies in "the management of the working time" through
negotiations between employers and employees.
</P>
<P>
The French national association of employers CNPF strongly
opposes the law, and some regional associations of employers have
vowed to "go to war" with the government over the issue.
</P>
<P>
If adopted by the National Assembly, or parliament, the law
will oblige all enterprises to start observing 35-hour work week
from year 2000.
</P>
<P>
A poll in Wednesday's Liberation daily suggests that two out of
three Frenchmen will accept a reduction of work week time if that
really leads to the creation of more jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
