<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Threatens Former President With Legal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today joined Truth and Reconciliation Commission
(TRC) Chairman Desmond Tutu in a threat of bringing charges
against former state president P W Botha if he refuses to appear
before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
The law should take its course if Botha persisted in his
refusal, South African Press Association quoted Mandela as saying
in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Botha was served with a third subpoena last week to testify
before the TRC on December 19 on the role of the former State
Security Council (SSC), which he chaired at the height of the
apartheid conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We would like the rule of law to be respected, No one is
above the law," Mandela told reporters after meeting a Dutch
Reformed Church delegation to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
"If all persuasion fails, the law must take its course," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the founding bill of the TRC, a person could face fines
or up to two years of imprisonment or both for disobeying a
subpoena.
</P>
<P>
Botha, who was president between 1984 and 1989, has repeatedly
said that he would not comply with a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
He also refused to apologize for the role of his government,
which vehemently implemented apartheid policies.
</P>
<P>
He escaped charges against him after he failed to appear at
the second round of SSC hearings last Friday in Cape Town owing
to a defection in the second subpoena.
</P>
<P>
Botha defied his first subpoena at the first round of SSC
hearings in Johannesburg last month on the grounds of bad health.
</P>
<P>
He told an Afrikaans newspaper in mid-November that he would
rather be charged than appear before the TRC and that he would
not seek amnesty at the TRC, which he called a "circus". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
