<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnia Peace Conference Concludes in Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- An international conference on
Bosnia was concluded here today with Western nations vowing to
force improved compliance with the Dayton peace accord from the
Bosnian parties.
</P>
<P>
But the two-day meetings had to adopt its final communique
without the participation of serb leaders who walked out of the
talks earlier today in protest against a Western demand to
negotiate the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Leaving the event were Federal Yugoslav Foreign Ministry
Director Dragomir Vucicevic, Bosnian Serb President Biljana
Plavsic and the Serb member of Bosnia's collective presidency,
Momcilo Krajisnik.
</P>
<P>
What prompted them to quit was the inclusion of Western demands
in the final's communique that Belgrade negotiate with ethnic
Albanians in its Kosovo region to defuse ethnic tensions.
</P>
<P>
"Dealing with the Kosovo issue at such a conference amounts to
indirect support for separatism and also terrorism," said
Vucicevic in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He also said that his government would not approve and did not
feel bound by the conference's 28-page final document because of
the inclusion of the Kosovo paragraph. However he also noted that
this did not mean that Belgrade would not back compliance with the
Dayton peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, who chaired the meetings,
told reporters that he regretted the Serb walk-out but stressed
that it would not have a direct impact on what had been achieved
in the meetings
</P>
<P>
Among the concrete results achieved was an approval from
Bosnian leaders of a common passport and citizenship for Bosnia, a
long-sought decision which has yet to be approved by the Bosnian
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The conference also approved strengthened power for the chief
international coordinator for Bosnia reconstruction, Carlos
Westendorf, who would be able to take binding decisions if the
Bosnian parties can not agree among themselves on issues such as a
common national flag, common car license plates as well as the
timing, location, and chairmanship of meetings of the common
institutions in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the meetings at a news conference, Kinkel said the
final document had made it clear to the Bosnian parties that
international assistance would remain conditional upon their
compliance with the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
"Those who comply will get help and those who do not will be
excluded," Kinkel warned.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing news conference, Westendorf said: "There
are still many things to be done and we have to speed up the
process because there is not much time left." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
