<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police to Take Stern Action Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean police will
take any necessary stern actions to deal with incidents of
violence and general lawlessness, Home Affairs Minister Dumiso
Dabengwa warned here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters following violent protests which rocked
the capital on Tuesday, Dabengwa said Harare had the highest
number of violent incidents reported with 31 shops being looted
during the one-day nationwide mass action organized by the
Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions to protest against heavy taxes.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We arrested 14 people in Harare for looting and they
will soon be appearing in court."
</P>
<P>
Three police vehicles and a national army van had been burnt
while at least eight private motor vehicles were stoned in the
capital on Tuesday, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said at least five police officers suffered minor injuries
while another police officer received serious head injuries
during the violence which broke out.
</P>
<P>
The exact cost of the damage is not yet clear as most
businesses and individuals are still evaluating the extent of
damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President of Zimbabwe National Chamber of Commerce
Danny Meyer today said that loss of revenue as a result of
Tuesday's mass protests against crippling taxes ran into millions
of dollars and affected not only the business community but the
fisc as well.
</P>
<P>
He noted that conflict resolution should be discussed at the
table, not the streets.
</P>
<P>
"If we want Zimbabwe to be a winning nation we must talk with
each other and not to each other," Meyer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
