<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Current Account Trade Deficit Shoots Up in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. current account
deficit shot up 11.4 percent to 42.2 billion U.S. dollars in the
third quarter of this year as Japanese investors sharply retreated
from their purchases of U.S. Treasury securities.
</P>
<P>
The deficit under the current account, the broadest measure of
U.S. foreign trade, rose from a seasonally adjusted 37.9 billion
dollars in the second quarter to 42.2 billion dollars in the
third, the Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
This was the highest level in a year. The shortfall for 1997
was mounting at an annual rate of 160 billion dollars as compared
with an actual deficit of 148.2 billion dollars in 1996. If
realized, 1997 would mark the worst current account trade
performance in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The current account includes not only trade in goods and
services but also investment flows between countries and foreign
aid.
</P>
<P>
The deterioration in the deficit partly reflects a currency
crisis that began in Thailand this Summer and spread to other
countries in the region this Fall. Sharp currency devaluations
have curtailed Asians' purchasing power and that's hurt U.S.
exports. Meanwhile, Asian nations have pushed to increase their
exports.
</P>
<P>
During the third quarter, the U.S. department reported a two
percent increase to 21.9 billion dollars in its surplus in
services such as tourism and consulting fees.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth was not enough to compensate for a 9.4
percent rise to 51.5 billion dollars in the deficit for goods and
a 2.3 percent increase, to 3.3 billion dollars, in the outflow of
investment income to foreign holders of U.S. assets. Besides, the
category that includes foreign aid rose 5.9 percent to 9.2 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The department said the big drop in Japanese purchases of
Treasury securities was mostly offset by an increase in European
purchases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
