<HEADLINE> ADB Think Tank Set Up in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Institute, a think tank and high-level training center affiliated
with the Manila-based bank, was opened here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
ADB President Mitsuo Sato told a press conference that the
Institute will engage in development research and provide
management training for top-level policy-makers and officials from
the bank's developing member states.
</P>
<P>
The institute will examine diverse social and economic issues
across the Asia and Pacific region by collaborating with other
institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Such work will lead to an expanded knowledge base and a wider
dissemination of development lessons and skills, all of which is
vital for the future development of the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
Jesus Estanislao, former Philippine finance secretary and the
first dean of the institute, said in his message that the
institute will help ADB's developing member states identify
development strategies suited to their particular conditions, and
facilitate the practical applications of these strategies through
applied research and training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
