<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran: Thaw in Tehran-Cairo Ties Crucial to Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami said here Wednesday that resuming and broadening amicable
ties between Tehran and Cairo can be a prelude to new developments
in the Middle East and in the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa on the fringe of the ongoing Islamic summit.
</P>
<P>
Iran cut off its relations with Egypt after it signed peace
accord with Israel under the brokerage of the United States in
1979. Represented only by interest sections in each other's
capital, the two have yet to recover full diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
In a conciliatory tone, Khatami said Tehran highly respects
Cairo, adding political disagreements are nothing but natural and
should not affect the historical and cultural common bonds
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Civilized people agree on disagreements," Khatami said, adding
the two sides should settle their disputes rationally.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite disagreement over the Middle East peace
process, Iran has never tried to impose its views on any country
or individual.
</P>
<P>
However, most neighboring Arab countries saw Iran as a threat
to their security in the 1980s for its advocacy of exporting
Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said Iran opposes the peace process as the trend of
affairs has proven that it is highly unlikely for anyone to come
to terms with Israel.
</P>
<P>
He lauded the recent Egyptian stance -- which has become more
and more critical of Israeli government's hardline policies
blamed for the stalemate in the peace-making.
</P>
<P>
The president called the Egyptian people as brothers and
expressed the hope that Iran and Egypt act as two pivots for
peace, progress and development in the region and the world.
</P>
<P>
As the first Egyptian foreign minister to visit Iran in nearly
two decades, Moussa conveyed President Hosni Mubarak's
congratulations to Khatami on his election as president.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak himself refrained from turning up at the three-day
summit of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) which
opened Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing their long-standing cultural and historical common
bonds, Moussa said his country always regards Iran as a very
great and important country in the region whose determining role
cannot be ignored.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt has long desired to have close and amicable
ties with Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
