<HEADLINE> EU Official Welcomes Call for Aerospace Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU)
official Wednesday welcomed the call for a restructuring of
Europe's defense and aerospace sectors by Europe's three leading
aerospace-manufacturing countries.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl,
French President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
issued an urgent appeal Tuesday to consolidate the industry into a
combined civil-defense company to compete on a world-wide scale with
its American rivals.
</P>
<P>
Martin Bangemann, EU commissioner in charge of industry,
said he was satisfied with the statement.
</P>
<P>
He said, "this initiative is a concrete step in the direction"
outlined by the EU's executive body, the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the three key EU member countries proposed expanding
the European Airbus consortium into an integrated company that
would also produce fighter jets, helicopters and missiles.
</P>
<P>
They also asked for a detailed timetable and a clear plan for
the consolidation to be presented in less than four months.
</P>
<P>
Bangemann said the EU executive would take necessary measures
at the European level in order to facilitate such structuring.
</P>
<P>
He also welcomed the involvement of other companies and other
European nations in the expansion.
</P>
<P>
The Airbus consortium, which groups the civilian aircraft
industries of France, Germany, Britain and Spain, has over 30
percent of the world market for civilian jets with more than 100
seats, and wants to increase that share to 50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
