<HEADLINE> Paris, Brussels Linked With Faster Rail Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Paris and Brussels, 300
kilometers apart, are about 30 minutes closer on a new European
version of "Bullet Train" premiered on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The train, known as Thalys, is initially commissioned to travel
between the two European capitals, at up to 300 kilometers per
hour, covering the distance in an hour and 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Its commercial service is to start on Sunday, with departures
every hour in each direction and every half hour at peak periods.
</P>
<P>
In what a major European newspaper called as "a new era of
high-speed travel" down the road, the train could branch out from
Brussels to further reach other cities in northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Under a current plan, along the extended route will be Antwerp
and Liege of Belgium, Rotterdam and Amsterdam of the Netherlands,
and Cologne of Germany.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held at the Gare du Nord station in Paris to
inaugurate the rail service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
