<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: Seven Million Doses of Vaccine Available to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- There are seven million doses
of meningococcal meningitis vaccine, plus an equal number of
autodestruct syringes, stockpiled and available to combat
meningitis in the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
Funding mechanisms are also in place to allow countries, which
may experience shortfalls in their own vaccine stocks during the
upcoming meningitis season, to have quick access to the ICG
stockpile and at a preferential price, according to a press
release issued by the World Health Organization (WHO) here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ICG, the International Coordination Group, had a two-day
meeting at WHO headquarters in Geneva on December 8-9.
</P>
<P>
The ICG was set up in 1997 for meningitis control in Africa by
WHO, the United Nations Children's Fund, the Federation of the
International Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies, Medecins Sans
Frontieres, as well as international nongovernmental
organizations, technical partners from WHO Collaborating Centers
and manufacturers of meningitis vaccine and autodestruct syringes.
</P>
<P>
The meningitis season normally runs from approximately December
to April and in the 1996 season, which ended in April 1996, there
was a record 150,000 cases of meningitis reported in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Meningitis epidemics occur in irregular cycles lasting a number
of years and therefore, the ICG confirmed, the same African
countries which have suffered over the past two years, as well as
neighboring countries, may experience large outbreaks again this
year.
</P>
<P>
The five countries to which the ICG made emergency supplies
available during the 1997 season were Burkina Faso, Gambia, Ghana,
Mali and Togo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
