<HEADLINE> Dutch Minister Shocked at Jewish Gold Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Dutch Finance Minister Gerrit
Zalm was shocked at a reported 1968 private sale to civil servants
in his ministry of valuables belonging to deported Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
De Groene Amsterdammer, a weekly, said the gold and silver
items, held in the safe of the Nazi-controlled Lippman &AMP; Rosenthal
Bank in Amsterdam, were offered at 1958 appraisal prices.
</P>
<P>
In some cases, it said, their purchasing rights were balloted.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Zalm said he could not believe this had ever
happened and would look into it.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed his disbelief in a letter to the lower
house of parliament, in which he was also responded to questions
about the plundering of Jewish citizens by soldiers of Nazi
Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
