<HEADLINE> France on Frontline Fighting Greenhouse Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine said today that France is on the frontline in controlling
greenhouse gas emission and is the locomotive of Europe in its
campaign for reduction of such gases at the Kyoto conference.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that with its nuclear electric power centers and
its policy emphasizing the saving of energy, France has set an
example in the control of greenhouse gases, which are blamed for
destroying the ozone layer of the earth and causing global
warming.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on the nuclear energy policy of France at
the National Assembly, or parliament, the minister said that among
developed countries, France contributes the least to the emission
of greenhouse gases on a global scale.
</P>
<P>
This gives France credit at the Kyoto conference on controlling
the emission of such gases and helps it defend the position of
Europe for cutting by 15 percent greenhouse gas emission by all
countries around the world.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kyoto, Japan, said that the 140 countries
attending the conference are approaching an agreement to reduce by
6-9 percent the emission of greenhouse gases, as the United States
is yielding to the pressure from European Union countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
