<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Saudi Mediation Between Iran, US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Deputy Foreign
Minister Javad Zarif today denied any mediation efforts by Saudi
Arabia between Iran and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the venue of the summit of the
Organization of Islamic Conference here, Zarif said there has been
no discussion between Iran and Saudi Arabia over the kingdom's
offer to mediate between Iran and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
He made the denial after Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn
Abdul-Aziz has been quoted by media reports as saying that if
asked by the U.S., Saudi Arabia is willing to mediate between Iran
and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The Saudi prince is here to attend the three-day Islamic summit
which opened Tuesday. He also held talks with Iran's supreme
leader Ali Khamenei Tuesday night, during which the two sides
expressed willingness to iron out their differences.
</P>
<P>
The moves are believed to reflect the improvement of relations
between the two Gulf giants, which have been at odds on a series
of issues since the Iranian Islamic Revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
They have severe disputes over Iran's incitement of revolution
in the kingdom after the Islamic Revolution, Saudi support for
Iraq during the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq War, and Saudi support for
U.S. military presence in the Gulf region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
