<HEADLINE> WFP Starts to Assist Flood-Hit Kenyans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food Program
(WFP) today started airlifting urgently needed food and other
items to almost 300,000 people in Kenya's worst flood-hit areas,
said a WFP report issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The WFP operation is expected to last one month with a total
of 1,000 tons of relief cargo including bulk foods, blankets,
drugs, plastic sheeting, seeds, cooking sets and kerosene to be
delivered to flood victims in eastern and coastal Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which will cost 7.2 million U.S. Dollars, is a
direct response to an appeal from the Kenyan government late last
month to help ease the devastating flood situation in the region
where people have been cut off from their regular sources of
supplies.
</P>
<P>
Even if the rains cease now, it will be until early January
that road communication can be restored there and Wajir and parts
of Tana River District, the worst flood-destroyed areas, are
likely to be isolated for longer time, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Extraordinary heavy rains caused by the El Nino weather
pattern have halted agricultural recovery in a majority parts of
Kenya from the previous drought brought about by the failure of
two rainy seasons in the country in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, household and commercial food stocks have
reportedly almost run out and prices for the remaining available
commodities are skyrocketing especially in the flood-affected
areas.
</P>
<P>
"Reports indicate that in a number of areas such as southern
Wajir and Garsen division of Tana River district, the situation
has if anything deteriorated since the time of the government
appeal," said Mike Sackett, the Country Director of Kenya.
</P>
</TEXT>
