<HEADLINE> Yearender: Nigerian Economy Needs More Than </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Various statistics show that
the Nigerian government has made further headway in 1997 in its
four-year-old efforts to bring order and stability into the
economy.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation rate, which stood at more than 100
percent in 1993 and 28 percent in 1996, has dropped to 13.7
percent by the end of August this year, which is two percent
lower than the government's 15.5 percent target for 1997.
</P>
<P>
In his November 17 national broadcast marking his four years
in power, the head of state, General Sani Abacha announced that
the latest inflation rate is now 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have attributed the sliding inflation rate to the
government's tight fiscal policy. The 70 billion Naira (about 886
million U.S. Dollars) budgetary deficit of 1994 had been replaced
by a surplus of 37 billion Naira (468 million Dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
For an economy which depends heavily on crude oil export for
revenue-generating and imports most consumer goods, the stability
of the currency is certainly important to the macro-economic
stability.
</P>
<P>
The government has also done well in this aspect, thanks to
the establishment in 1995 of the Autonomous Foreign Exchange
Market, at which the U.S. Dollar is sold to commercial banks
through auctions.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the first 10 months of the year, the exchange rate
of Naira against dollar had been moving between 80 to 85 Naira to
one Dollar, though the Naira appreciated under pressure to 79
Naira against one Dollar in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the external sector is equally encouraging.
The country's foreign reserves, which kept growing in the last
two years, shot up to eight billion Dollars by September,
according to the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the government expects an economic growth rate of
about four percent in 1997, which, though lower than the set goal
of five percent, is the highest in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
While the government's success in stabilizing the economy
received general recognition, almost all the people agreed that
the Nigerian economy now faces another menace. It is now in a
serious stagnation.
</P>
<P>
The manufacture industry is perhaps the most miserable sector
of the economy. A mid-year report of the Manufacturers
Association of Nigeria (MAN) said the sector's unsold inventory
swelled to 4.6 billion Naira (58 million Dollars) by the end of
June, 13.7 percent up from the level at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the sector's capacity utilization declined
33.9 percent to an alarming 29.4 percent. As a result, about
12,000 jobs were lost in the sector.
</P>
<P>
MAN has repeatedly blamed its misfortune on the worsening
business environment: the population's poor purchasing power, the
increasing frequency of power failure, the shortage of petroleum
products and many more others.
</P>
<P>
MAN was right in pointing out the problems. But the other
sectors were having their own share of bad lucks.
</P>
<P>
The power sector has been suffering from acute shortage of
funds to repair its aging systems. Its operator, the National
Electric Power Authority (NEPA) has warned repeatedly of an
imminent nationwide blackout.
</P>
<P>
NEPA's thirst for fund was a joint product of underfunding by
the government and serious indebtedness to it by consumers.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that consumers nationwide now owe NEPA as much
as 15 billion Naira (190 million Dollars), so high that the
federal government had to set up a task force in October to help
recover the debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Nigerian Economy Needs More Than </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The oil industry, which
generated 98.2 percent of the country's export income in 1996,
suffered a loss as well in 1997.
</P>
<P>
While the sector's cash demand was put at 3.5 billion Dollars,
the government allocated only two billion Dollars in the budget,
though another one billion was agreed upon later after
negotiations between the government and the oil sector.
</P>
<P>
To make it worse, the government insisted that the Nigeria
National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) must account for its
spending in 1996 before fresh fund is released. As the NNPC
failed to do so, the release was much delayed.
</P>
<P>
This has forced NNPC's foreign partners, which produce the
majority of the country's crude oil, to scale down their
production and in some cases, exploration schemes were cancelled.
Analysts have warned that this will have an adverse effect on
Nigeria's long-term oil strategy.
</P>
<P>
An immediate victim of this policy is the country's aging
refineries, which have been due for major repairs for years.
</P>
<P>
When it was clear that the refineries could no longer meet the
nation's needs for fuel and that fuel shortage was developing
into a nation crisis, the government ordered fuel import in June.
It is expected that Nigeria, one of the largest oil producers in
the world, will continue importing fuel in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Under all these misfortunes, many common Nigerians have
complained of little improvement in their living standard. Though
prices are increasing at slow pace, many basic goods are still
beyond their reach. There is no power, no petrol and no traffic.
The government's figures of economic improvement appears
suspicious to them.
</P>
<P>
To improve the funding and management of the country's many
infrastructure departments, the government has taken some steps
to liberalize them.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization of the telecommunications sector, which
began in 1995, saw a major breakthrough in October 1997, with the
signing of a network interconnection agreement between the
Nigeria Telecommunications (NITEL) and the private Multi-Links,
ending NITEL's decades of monopoly in wired telephone service.
</P>
<P>
Rescue is also coming to the country's ailing refineries, with
reports that talks were on to sell some major refineries to Shell
and other multi-national oil companies.
</P>
<P>
Some groups, however, have criticized the government of being
too slow on the road to liberalization. They want the government
to open the power sector to private businesses and merge the
official exchange rate of 22 Naira to one dollar to the
Autonomous Foreign Exchange Market, among other things.
</P>
<P>
This, of course, has been resisted by the government, which
prefers a more prudent approach because of its political
fragility as military government is set to quit from the scene in
less than one year's time.
</P>
<P>
General Sani Abacha did promise in his November 17 national
broadcast to give Nigerians a more reliable power supply and to
boost their purchasing power in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The government seems to have realized that any economic
achievements will be pale and unconvincing if the true purchasing
power of the people remains unimproved.
</P>
<P>
The biggest concern at the moment, however, is how the Abacha
administration's economic feat will survive the political
uncertainties expected in 1998, as the transition to civil rule
program reaches its final stage. Faster growth in 1998 is out of
the question. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
