<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK'S Moves on Regulation, Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 10 (Xinhua) - Britain is to take moves to
improve co-ordination of regulatory activity in the period before
formal creation of a single financial services regulator and about
Millennium Risk.
</P>
<P>
Speaking today about the FSA's (Financial Services Authority)
developing agenda at a Regulation Conference, its Chairman Howard
Davies said: "We will take every opportunity we can to improve the
co-ordination of regulatory activity."
</P>
<P>
He said that means working towards a single approach on
responsibilities of senior management, co-ordinating FSA's
assessments of the challenges posed to financial institutions by
EMU and promoting regulatory action on Millennium risk.
</P>
<P>
The Year 2000 is an important business issue for financial
firms and markets. They all wish, in their own interests, to
maintain continuity and quality of service for their customers.
</P>
<P>
The Chairman said, but the Year 2000 is also a regulatory
issue. It has implications for investor protection, for the
prudential health of businesses, for market integrity and for
investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
"This is because an institution's failure to prepare for the
Millennium could leave investors or depositors unable to access
their money and asset, or degradation of customer records and
even, in the extreme, business collapse," he warned.
</P>
<P>
For regulators, just as for firms, "prevention" is far better
than "cure", Davies argued, saying "every financial firm should
have completed its remedial action and tested its systems by the
end of 1998". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
