<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: West Africa Gears up to Promote Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The development of energy
supply in west Africa is expected to get a boost soon with the
completion of two multi-billion-U.S.-Dollar projects in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
A hydroelectric power supply network is underway to connect
Senegal, Mali and Mauritania, while preparations are being made
to lay pipeline from Nigeria to Ghana, Benin and Togo for natural
gas transportation.
</P>
<P>
The hydropower project, estimated to cost a total of some 1.25
billion Dollars, involves the construction of three electric
carrier line interconnecting the three countries.
</P>
<P>
It will have its source from the Manatali Hydroelectric Dam in
Mali which is now being developed to produce 800 gwh per year.
Senegal is expected to consume 33 percent of this output, with
Mali and Mauritania sharing 52 and 15 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the European Union (EU) and European
Investment Bank approved 40 billion CFA (about 70 million
Dollars) to be injected by Europe for the implementation of the
project.
</P>
<P>
The three countries has set up a body known as Organization
for the Development of River Senegal for the construction of the
project.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a multinational company has been established to
oversee the execution of the 315-million-Dollar west African gas
pipeline project.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the rich natural gas resources in Nigeria will
be transported to its neighbors to meet their energy demands.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the World Bank-backed gas project, the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) has conducted a study
to identify the renewable energy requirement of its 16 member
countries in the area of solar, biomass and wind energy.
</P>
<P>
According to ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Kouyate, work
is progressing on the preparation of a solar and energy map which
will highlight solar and wind energy potential in each country,
region and area.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS member states also target at establishing a
sub-regional electricity grid for providing energy for countries
which have no hydropower stations and no petroleum resources,
Kouyate said.
</P>
<P>
A protocol on the project has been signed by leaders of member
countries.
</P>
<P>
When the ambition is realized, west African countries will
have a radical improvement in energy supply, therefore
accelerating the economic development in the sub-region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
