<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Leaving Summit, Not Due to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic summit Spokesman
Javad Zarif said today that Turkish President Suleyman Demirel is
leaving here ahead of schedule, but not due to displeasure at the
criticism of his country's close ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Zarif, who is also Iran's deputy foreign minister, said that
Demirel's early departure "can be due to some other engagements
rather than the reported unhappiness of Turkey over some of the
resolutions."
</P>
<P>
Turkey is under pressure during sessions of the three-day
Eighth Summit of the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC),
which is to be concluded Thursday, for its close relations with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from the 55 OIC members are attending the three-day
conference during which they described Israel as the "Zionist
regime," "usurper of Arab lands" and "occupier of Qods"
(Jerusalem) which is holy to Muslims, calling for isolation of the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Turkey signed two military agreements with Israel last year,
provoking criticism by Muslim countries especially Arab nations
who regard the cooperation as a threat to them.
</P>
<P>
However, the Turkish leader today told Iranian reporters that
differences within the Islamic world are a natural thing. He said,
"when one speaks of the Islamic world, he speaks of different
peoples with a variety of socio-economic conditions. Therefore, a
single definite and uniform solution can not be adapted for all of
them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
