<HEADLINE> BA in Dogfight With Rival Lufthansa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 10 (Xinhua) - British Airways (BA) has taken
rival Lufthansa to the European Commission over an alleged "dirty
tricks" campaign.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the EU's free trade commissioner in Brussels,
Karel Van Miert, BA's German arm accused Lufthansa of subsidizing
price-cutting on internal German routes in order to drive the
British airline out of the skies over Germany.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche BA operates services on eight of the busiest 10
internal German routes and is second to Lufthansa in Germany, with
14 percent of the domestic flights market.
</P>
<P>
It contends Lufthansa's tactics of sustaining losses to secure
a monopoly in the internal market violate the Treaty of Rome and
European single market rules.
</P>
<P>
"Lufthansa's price-setting strategy is very selective and
systematic," the BA letter alleged.
</P>
<P>
"Selective, because Lufthansa does not change its prices on the
routes it operates without competition, Systematic, because
Lufthansa copies the slightest price readjustment by Deutsche BA,"
it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
