<HEADLINE> S. Africa's ANC Releases Nomination List for Top </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) today released its nomination
list for top posts to be contested at next week's national
conference, the South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
ANC Deputy President Thabo Mbeki is set to succeed President
Nelson Mandela as party chief, and National Union of Mineworkers
General Secretary Kgalema Motlanthe is the sole nominee for ANC
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
No nominations from the floor are allowed for the two posts.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing National Chairman Jacob Zuma has been nominated for
the post of deputy president by all nine ANC provincial
structures, although he may be challenged by Winnie
Madikizela-Mandela if she is nominated from the floor.
</P>
<P>
The national chairman's post will be contested by Patrick
Lekota and Steve Tshwete, while Mendi Msinmang and Popo Molefe
will vie for treasurer-general, the ANC Nominations Committee
said.
</P>
<P>
The only two women nominated by the ANC's nine provinces for
the top executive positions, Thenjiwe Mtintso and Mavivi
Myakayaka-Manzini, will contest the deputy secretary-general's
post.
</P>
<P>
Nominations Committee coordinator Charles Nqakulu told a press
briefing that under ANC constitution, only provinces had the
right to nominate candidates for ANC's National Executive
Committee.
</P>
<P>
However, a delegate to the conference had the right to
nominate any person whose name had not been proposed by the
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Certain constitutional amendments were being proposed to
govern nominations from the floor, Nqakulu said.
</P>
<P>
The ANC constitution currently allows for such a nomination to
be supported by a show of hands of 10 percent of voting
delegates. The proposed amendment will push the percentage to
either 25 or 30 percent. The nomination vote process might also
change from a show of hands to endorsement in writing.
</P>
<P>
The process of nominations from the floor may be crucial for
Madikizela-Mandela's bid for the deputy presidency, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
If an endorsement is by a show of hands, delegates might be
reluctant to show support for Madikizela-Mandela in front of the
national leadership, while having their support preserved in
writing may also put some delegates off.
</P>
<P>
The reputation of Madikizela-Mandela, former wife of Mandela,
was marred to some extent as she was implicated in 18 cases of
human rights violations at a nine-day hearing on the role of the
so-called Mandela United Football Club, her former bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
Provinces had also submitted names of nominees for the 60
directly elected positions on the policy-making National
Executive Committee, Nqakulu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mkapa Expresses Determination to Reduce Reliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa said today his country will strive to reduce
reliance on donors and further economic and political reforms.
</P>
<P>
Opening a three-day Consultative Group Meeting (CGM) for
Tanzania and its donors at the Sheraton Hotel here, Mkapa said
that Tanzania will make efforts to achieve self-reliance through
self-development.
</P>
<P>
However, development of the country is hindered by the burden
of external debt, which had reached as high as 8.1 billion US
Dollars by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
The president last Saturday appealed for debt relief to
Tanzania, saying the country's debt was unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is spending 37 percent of its revenue
on debt repayment, a burden that fails to finance important
social services like education and health adequately.
</P>
<P>
While appealing for debt relief, the president assured
participants at the CGM today that Tanzania will press ahead with
economic and political reforms simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made in reforming finance, social services and
other sectors, pushing privatization process and combating
corruption, he added.
</P>
<P>
CGM is a forum at which major donor countries and multilateral
institutions collectively meet individual developing countries to
review donor-funded projects and agree on future terms on
co-operation. The meetings are normally held in Paris, but is
being held in Tanzania for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa expressed thanks to international donors which have been
supporting the country for so long since the independence of the
country in 1961.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania scores good marks on macro-economic performance with
inflation declining to 15.8 percent from 25.1 percent in January
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's success to curbing inflation despite adverse
weather conditions experienced during the last quarter of 1996
and early this year, is attributed to cash-management budget and
tight fiscal discipline.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats told the press that cash-management budget and
fiscal discipline are likely to draw sympathetic response for
appeals for debt relief.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries attending the meeting include Australia,
Austria, Belgium, Britain, Canada, China, Denmark, Finland,
France, Ireland, Japan, Kuwait, the Netherlands, Norway, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia, Sweden, Switzerland, United Arab Emirates and the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
