<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills 9 in E. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Nine people were killed by
cholera in eastern Uganda last week, The New Vision reported
today.
</P>
<P>
James Muwanga, a local council chairman, confirmed to the
newspaper that 47 other people was sick and four among them have
been admitted to Kigandaalo Health Center.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic was detected on December 4 when three people fell
sick and died a few hours later.
</P>
<P>
Muwanga said all the patients have the same symptoms -- vomiting
and acute diarrhoea. He complained of lack of transport to take the
patients in time to hospitals due to the roads damaged by heavy rains
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Local council has sent several reports to District Medical
Officer (DMO).
</P>
<P>
Jennifer Namusobya, the acting DMO of the district, said her
office has received the reports and has sent an official to assess the
situation in the affected area.
</P>
<P>
Lack of latrines in the affected area is one of the reasons to the
epidemic, the acting DMO said.
</P>
<P>
The situation was similar in Kisese district in the West and
Rakai district in the center.
</P>
<P>
Villages in Karusanda sub-county have been hit and the
latrines were destroyed by floods caused by torrential rains,
said John Baluku, St. John's Ambulance Chairman, Kasese District.
</P>
<P>
The bushes were litered with feces, the ambulance chairman
visiting the affected area said.
</P>
<P>
The officials of DMO office confirmed dysentery cases in the
sub-county.
</P>
<P>
Local officials in Kyotera Town, Rakai District, said the only
public latrine near the market in the town was closed due to
filling-up. The local officials feared the situation would result in
an outbreak of diarrhoea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
