<HEADLINE> Jordan Expels 7 Iraqi Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today expelled seven
Iraqi diplomats after the Iraqi authorities executed four young
Jordanians Monday on charge of smuggling auto spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister Jawad Anani this noon summoned
Iraqi Ambassador Nouri Elwayess and told him to decrease the
number of the embassy staff from 15 to eight, Jordan's official
news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
The seven Iraqi diplomats have to leave Amman in a week,
according to Petra.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordan has recalled its charge d'affaires in
Baghdad Adel Sweidan back home in order to listen to his report on
the execution, said Petra.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Acting Prime Minister Abdullah Ensour said today that
Iraq did not inform Jordan on the trial of the four Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
The execution came as a "sudden" news to Jordan as the kingdom
is rallying behind Baghdad for lifting of the U.N. sanctions on
Iraq imposed after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, Ensour was quoted
by Petra as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government will adopt more actions later at proper times,
said Ensour, insisting that the mere issuance of official
statements condemning the execution is far from enough to explain
the embarrassed situation of the government.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the House of Representatives Saad Hail El-Sorour
 today told Petra that the execution is short of legal evidence
and violates the principle of good neighborliness and Arab
fraternity.
</P>
<P>
Jordan used to adopt a way of negotiation with other Arab
countries, including Iraq, when it came to legal issues, said
Sorour.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the Iraq's action is wierd and surprising, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian senate and government have also issued official
statements to condemn the execution.
</P>
<P>
The government statement on Tuesday said that Iraq did not
answer Jordanian officials' efforts to enlist information about
the nature of the charge. Jordanian officials failed to dissuade
the Iraqi authority from carrying out the "unjust" decision to
execute the Jordanians, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement insisted that the Jordanian should only be
punished with fine or prison term even if the charge proved to be
true.
</P>
<P>
The statement from the Senate today said that the execution
contradicted with the principles of good neighborliness and Arab
fraternity.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has not reacted to Jordan's condemnation.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Iraq used to be firm allies before and during the
1990-91 Gulf Crisis. But after that, the bilateral ties suffered a
setback as Jordan distanced itself away from Iraq to end
international alienation.
</P>
<P>
However, the ties have been picking up in recent years as Iraq
began to provide the kingdom with more oil at discount prices and
kept increasing the volume of imports from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is a main supplier of humanitarian goods for Baghdad
under the U.N.-Iraqi oil-for-food deal signed in May last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
