<HEADLINE> Iraqi Foreign Minister Appreciates Islamic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf expressed his country's appreciation of the
ongoing Islamic summit here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the second day of the three-day eighth
summit of the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC), Sahhaf
said the summit is taking a step forward in strengthening the OIC
and refocusing attention on the basic and strategic causes of the
Islamic nations.
</P>
<P>
On the draft resolutions on Iraq due to be discussed at the
summit, he said some drafts call on the Arab and Islamic states to
help relieve the hardships of the Iraqis caused by the sanctions
imposed by the United Nations in 1990.
</P>
<P>
He said another draft emphasizes the respect of Iraq's
sovereignty, integrity and security, which is a strong reference
to Ankara's military operations against Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf is a member of the Iraqi delegation led by Vice
President Taha Yassin Ramadan to the OIC summit. This is Iraq's
first high level delegation to visit Iran since the war between
the two countries from 1980 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
On Iraqi ties with Iran, Sahhaf said that practical steps have
been taken to help ease the tensions in the bilateral relations
and further resolve the existing thorny problems.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Iran have held talks on exchanging prisoners of war
and some other issues and achieved a little progress. But their
positions on the problem still keep far apart. They accuse each
other of holding far more POWs than believed. 
</P>
