<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mary Robinson: Universal Declaration Must be Given </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Human Rights, Mary Robinson, stressed today that
the Universal Declaration of Human Rights must be given practical
effect.
</P>
<P>
In her massage to the occasion of the Human Rights Day,
December 10, Robinson said Human Rights Day should be a time to
reaffirm our commitment to work for change and to demonstrate that
the principles of the United Nations Charter and the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights are not theoretical or abstract.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that this must be given practical effect with the
results measured by the improved well-being of individuals around
the world.
</P>
<P>
The Commissioner said this Human Rights Day begins the
year-long review of the Vienna Declaration and Program of
Action, a time when the United Nations system and all governments
seriously assess their successes and short-comings in living up to
the solemn obligations made at the World conference on Human
Rights in 1993.
</P>
<P>
She said this year should be a year of discussion and debate on
the continuing relevance of international human rights standards
in the international system, in national administration and the
work of civil society.
</P>
<P>
Robinson encouraged purposeful debate on economic, social and
cultural rights and the right to development in ways which open up
better understanding on how these human rights can be implemented
in international and national programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
