<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Negotiators Meet to Discuss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli and Palestinian
peace negotiating teams held talks here today in an effort to
narrow their gap so to achieve progress in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two teams were headed respectively by Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy and deputy head of Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen).
</P>
<P>
The two leaders first held a half-hour private meeting before
holding enlarged talks joined by other senior negotiators and some
heads of the nine joint interim committees.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the joint news conference after the meeting, Levy
described the talks as being held "in a spirit of good-will and
mutual desire to see progress" in the peace process. "I want to
stress the desire that has been given and expressed by the
Palestinian side to find solutions to issues on our agenda," he
said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
Levy said the Israeli government is looking into various issues
concerning the peace process in order to "bring new impetus for
the peace process to create a different atmosphere and to
facilitate progress in all fields of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the sides are at an era when important
decisions should be made on many crucial issues. He was referring
to Israeli government's deliberations on the second troop
redeployment in the West Bank, guidelines on permanent talks,
time-out of settlements and the interim issues, such as opening
the Gaza airport, building a Gaza seaport and creating a safe
passage between Gaza Strip and West Bank.
</P>
<P>
On the second redeployment, Levy said the government will
convince the Knesset (Parliament) to approve the scope approved
by the cabinet. But he did not disclose when and what the cabinet
will come out with the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Levy announced that the joint negotiating teams will continue
their intensive talks Thursday in a bid to solve the remaining
differences on the interim issues. "I have no doubt that the
mutual efforts we are investing will indeed bear fruits in the
near future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abbas said both sides have made necessary efforts to push
forward the peace process in the right direction. He added that
the two sides will work intensively in order to achieve results in
the talks at the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
Today's talks were held under the shadow of a heated dispute
between the two sides over the PNA's attempt to conduct census in
the disputed East Jerusalem. Contrary to the wide speculation,
Levy denied that they have discussed the dispute over census.
</P>
<P>
But Levy made it clear that Israel regards the PNA attempt as a
unilateral step in violation of signed peace agreements. He said
although similar census was conducted before the January 1996
Palestinian elections as agreed by the sides, this time the PNA
did not contact Israel on the matter.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Israeli government will prevent the PNA
from taking census in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
