<HEADLINE> Liberian Police Hold Four over Murder of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Liberian police have arrested
four men in connection with the murder of an opposition member of
parliament and three members of his family, the Justice Ministry
said today in Monrovia, the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the four men were identified as
Isaac Whonnie, an aide-de-camp to President Charles Taylor, Moses
Jallah, who works for the Special Security Service (SSS) of the
executive mansion, and two civilians, Richmond Saydee and Kennedy
Fineboy.
</P>
<P>
"The culprits, irrespective of who they are, will be brought
to justice," said the minister, quoted by the British
Broadcasting Corporation (BBC).
</P>
<P>
SSS Director Colonel Benjamin Yeaten has been asked to help in
the investigation, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
According to the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN), Samuel Dokie, a
prominent Liberian political figure, first disappeared and was
later confirmed arrested, but on December 2, he was founded dead.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today said the charred corpses of
Dokie, his wife, sister and cousin, were found near the central
town of Gbarnga.
</P>
<P>
As investigation is still going on, the justice minister
warned the public against what he called premature judgement in
the murder case, saying, "no charges have been made."
</P>
<P>
A ministry statement also urged the Liberian press to stop
printing photographs of the corpses "to avoid prejudice".
</P>
<P>
After the minister finished reading the statement, reporters
were not allowed to ask questions, the BBC said, adding that
Taylor earlier pledged his government's commitment to equal
justice for all under the law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, NAN reported that many Liberians living in the
United States were shocked by the killing of Dokie, which seemed
to have destroyed the confidence they reposed on the democratic
process in the country.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted some leaders of Liberian groups as saying
that the unfortunate development would make many Liberians who
intended going back to contribute to the post-war peace-building
effort to have a second thought about it.
</P>
<P>
Late Dokie was an ally of President Taylor at the beginning of
his rebellion against the government of Samuel Doe, which
triggered off the Liberian civil war in the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
However, he fell out with Taylor, the then leader of a major
warring faction, complaining that Taylor did not want the war to
end.
</P>
<P>
The murder of Dokie also aroused complaints from various human
rights groups. Women groups moaning the killing today in
Monrovia called the day "Black Wednesday".
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, Taylor has appointed his former
rival Alhaji Kromah to the position of chairman of the newly
constituted National Reconciliation Commission.
</P>
<P>
Kromah, who is currently in the Guinean capital of Conakry,
has not responded to the appointment in the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
