<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Approves Plans on Border Guard Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The concept and overall idea
for developing the Federal Border Service (FPS) was approved today
by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, Director of Service Andrei
Nikolayev told reporters.
</P>
<P>
While the service plans to discontinue certain kinds of heavy
weaponry such as armored vehicles and artillery systems of caliber
greater than 82 millimeters, it will simultaneously "improve its
arsenal," in particular by developing a light armored vehicle
which could be serviced at conventional service stations,
Nikolayev said.
</P>
<P>
The FPS is manned to 97 percent of its intended capacity, with
an officer corps of 27,000, according to the director.
</P>
<P>
The FPS is looking for other sources because of insufficient
financing, Nikolayev said. Yeltsin instructed the government and
the Finance Ministry to keep the FPS properly financed in 1998.
Nikolayev quoted Yeltsin as saying, "Everybody must attend to his
business, the Armed Forces to defense and the FPS to border
security."
</P>
<P>
On the border problem with Georgia, the director said that
Russia will not move. He emphasized that the strategic tunnels in
the Daryal Canyon, the gateway into the Caucasus, rather than
border posts are at stake. 
</P>
