<HEADLINE> Special Committee Urged to be Set Up to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Germany's opposition Social
Democrats (SPD) and the Greens party today proposed to establish a
special parliamentary committee to probe the latest scandal that a
convicted neo-Nazi had been invited to address officers at an
elite defense academy.
</P>
<P>
German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe, whose resignation was
demanded by the SPD on Monday, also told the parliamentary defense
committee meeting today that there would be an investigation to
find out whether defense ministry officials were responsible for
the incident.
</P>
<P>
Manfred Roeder, 68, was invited in 1995 to speak at the Hamburg
Bundeswehr Leadership Academy. His subject was ethnic Germans who
populated Koenigsberg, the former capital of East Prussia, which
is now the Russian enclave of Kaliningrad, located between Poland
and the Baltic states.
</P>
<P>
Roeder was sentenced to 13 years in prison in 1982 for racist
bombings against immigrants. He was released on probation in 1990,
with his activities monitored by the country's anti-extremist
watchdog agency.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe has punished two senior officers for their failure to
investigate Roeder's background. He has stressed that no evidence
can now show that those responsible for Roeder's appearance were
aware of his history.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe today also announced that an independent panel of experts
would be set up to scrutinize the general morale of the
Bundeswehr. The German armed forces have been hit by a series of
scandals involving extreme rightist activities.
</P>
<P>
According to the Defense Ministry recently, more than 80
incidents involving neo-Nazi behavior have been under
investigation in the past year, which range from the possession of
far-right praopaganda to drunken assaults against foreigners
living in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe has insisted that all these were isolated cases and did
not mean that rightist extremism was rampant within the army.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary defense committee was today also informed of
a newly-discovered video which, made in 1990, depicted soldiers
giving the banned Hitler salute.
</P>
<P>
A videotape found earlier this year showed soldiers staging
mock executions and rapes as well as giving the Hitler salute and
making anti-Semitic remarks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
