<HEADLINE> US to Set Up Drug Court Institute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Barry McCaffrey, director
of the Office of National Drug Policy, has presented a 339,000
dollar initial grant to the National Association of Drug Court
Professionals to create a National Drug Court Institute to provide
training, research and education for 300 drug courts.
</P>
<P>
Judge Jeffery Tauber, association president, said about 75
percent of those who enroll in the drug court programs do not
return to criminal lives.
</P>
<P>
During the yuletide season, Tauber said prisoners released from
drug courts usually show their gratitude for the treatment that
has put their lives back together by writing "thank you" notes to
the judges.
</P>
<P>
The judge urged the government to offer alternatives to drug
addicts, rather than criminal terms.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey said the establishment of the drug courts, "coupled
with their judicial leadership, constitutes one of the most
monumental positive changes in the U.S. justice system relating to
drug offenders since World War II."
</P>
<P>
The association was formed in 1994 with a mission to reduce
substance abuse, crime and recidivism by promoting the
establishment and funding of drug courts and distribution
information.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey said drug courts provide an effective solution to
drug and drug-related crime through comprehensive supervision,
drug testing and treatment services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
