<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Joint Efforts to Solve Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has called on all
parties involved in the Cyprus problem, namely Greece, the Greek
Cypriots and the Turkish Cypriots, besides itself, to jointly
solve the issue, the Cyprus News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is not the only country which can propose a solution to
the protracted problem, Turkish Deputy Foreign Minister Inal Batu
said in an interview with London Greek Radio, according to the
agency.
</P>
<P>
"We need the contribution of at least three other sides, the
Turkish Cypriots, the Greek Cypriots and Athens and that's what we
are trying to achieve," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops landed
on the Mediterranean island and took over the northern third to
protect the ethnic minority of the Turkish Cypriots following an
abortive coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on plans by the Cypriot government to deploy
Russian-made missiles, Batu said that Turkey will not allow the
missiles to become threats to it.
</P>
<P>
"I am not saying that we will be hitting them or destroying
them, we will take measures which will make these missiles, if
they are bought, ineffective against our country as a threat," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia last January to buy a number
of anti-aircraft missiles. 
</P>
