<HEADLINE> UK Minister Resign Over Benefit Cuts to Lone Parents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A British minister resigned
today over welfare plans, dealing a blow to the Labor government
which came to power in May.
</P>
<P>
Malcolm Chisholm, a junior Scottish Office minister, handed his
resignation letter to Prime Minister Tony Blair and said he would
oppose the cuts of benefits to single mothers in a parliamentary
vote later in the day as the cuts were "an attack on some of the
poorest women in society."
</P>
<P>
Blair suffered a further revolt today when another Labor MP,
Gordon Prentice, stepped down as parliamentary private secretary
to Transport Minister Gavin Strang.
</P>
<P>
Other MPs were also stepping up their opposition to the benefit
plans and announced their intention to oppose the government.
</P>
<P>
The Labor wants to reduce state benefits for Britain's one
million lone parents by up to 11 pounds (18 US dollars) a week in
an attempt to encourage them to abandon welfare and go to work.
</P>
<P>
Although dozens of Labor MPs were opposed to the welfare plan,
Blair took a tough stand and was determined to see it through,
saying getting single mothers back to work was more important than
granting benefits.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is to help those lone parents off
benefits and into work," the prime minister told parliament.
</P>
<P>
"There are limited resources. When we came to power, we made it
quite clear we had to stick within existing budgets guidelines
because we weren't going to lose control of the money available,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
