<HEADLINE> European Shares Down on Weaker Asian Markets, Dow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all ended lower today, undermined by Asian markets' retreat and
Wall Street's opening losses as well as by a weaker dollar.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index closed nearly 1 percent or 46.6
points down at 5,130.7, but still managed to hold onto the key
5,100-point level.
</P>
<P>
Prices drifted lower as profit-takers stepped into after an
overnight sell-off on Asian markets. Losses were extended in
afternoon trading with Wall Street's further losses.
</P>
<P>
The downturn in London was led by banking stocks which
accounted for almost 40 percent of the FTSE 100 index's decline.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares ended 1.62 percent lower,
continuing a period of consolidation after recent gains.
</P>
<P>
"The losses in the Far East and Wall Street added some downward
pressure," one trader commented.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index was 67.64 points lower at 4,117.27 as a softer
dollar also weighed on the market.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris finished 27.22 points weaker at
2,932.18. Dealers said that the market was also dragged down by
profit-taking and falls on other world markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
