<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Climate Change Conference Wraps Up in Kyoto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations climate change
conference ended in Kyoto, western Japan, on Thursday by obliging
the developed countries to cut more on their greenhouse gas
emissions.
</P>
<P>
The gathering, of delegates from some 160 countries, was the
third of the kind to substantiate the U.N. Framework Convention on
Climate Change forged in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, in June 1992.
</P>
<P>
The conference was initially scheduled to close on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, its most important product, a protocol to cut global
gas emissions in the 2008-2012 period by an average of 5.2 percent
below the 1990 or 1995 levels, was not delivered until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After all-night rounds of stormy deliberations, negotiators at
the policy-making committee finally adopted the document at 10
a.m., and submitted it for approval by the plenary session.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, 38 industrialized countries are divided
into eight groups and different emission targets, ranging from an
8 percent reduction to a 10 percent rise, are set for each.
</P>
<P>
Among these groups, the 15-nation European Union (EU) is to cut
its emissions by 8 percent, the United States 7 percent and Japan
6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Greenhouse gases referred in the document are carbon dioxide
(CO2), methane, nitrous oxide, hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs),
perfluorocarbons (PFCs) and sulfur hexafluoride (SF6).
</P>
<P>
These gases, especially CO2 from burning fossil fuels such as
oil and coal, could trigger what is called "greenhouse effect" to
trap solar radiation heat within the Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the world's science community has provided
increasingly convincing evidences to pinpoint greenhouse gases
behind what is believed to be an ongoing trend of "global warming."
</P>
<P>
The Kyoto protocol stipulates that 1995 may be used as the base
year for HFCs, PFCs and SF6, as these man-made gases were hardly
produced before 1990, the base year used for the other three gases.
</P>
<P>
It also ratifies "joint implementation," in which an
industrialized country can invest in a developing country to cut
emissions and take those emission reductions into its own account.
</P>
<P>
Industrialized countries can also add to its account the
absorption of greenhouse gases by forests in achieving binding
commitments.
</P>
<P>
To help developing countries tackle global warming, the
document calls for the creation of a "clean development
mechanism," to legalize the sale of reductions in greenhouse gas
emissions by developing countries to industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was praised by Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary
Kanezo Muraoka, who described it as "an epoch-making first step
toward preventing global warming and preserving the global
environment."
</P>
<P>
Japanese industry officials, however, expressed pessimism about
the practicality of the emission reduction targets for
industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
To meet Japan's 6 percent cut target, they said, the Japanese
people will be urged to cut their energy use by more than 10
percent and to change their lifestyle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
