<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former French PM Suggests Constitutional Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Former French prime minister
Raymond Barre Thursday suggested a reform of the French
Constitution to avoid right-left cohabitation in the country's
political system.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview, Barre said that a division on top of
the state caused by the cohabitation is beginning to cause
problems in the country's national and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Could there be the means... through the constitutional
mechanism, to avoid this division at the summit of the state which,
in national and international field, begins to pose problems?" he
asked.
</P>
<P>
He said he was in favor of the idea to reduce the presidential
term from seven years to five years, and to have the legislative
elections held simutaneously with the presidential election,
although he admitted that this is not a "perfect formula."
</P>
<P>
France holds its presidential election every seven years and
legislative elections every five years.
</P>
<P>
Barre, who is from the centrist Union for French Democracy,
also doubted whether the cohabitation between President Jacques
Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin "will be long."
</P>
<P>
Raymond Barre worked as French prime minister from August of 1976
to May of 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
