<HEADLINE> UK PM to Meet Sinn Fein Leader with no Illusion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair was to meet Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams for the sake of
peace, a government spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister is under no illusions about the nature of
Sinn Fein but they are in the talks... Mr. Adams and his colleagues
will be treated in the same way as other parties in the talks,"
Blair's official spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister "is prepared to take risks for peace and he
believes the prospects are better than they have been for a
generation," he added.
</P>
<P>
The historic talks, to be held at 2:00 p.m. in No.10 Downing
Street, will be the first meeting in London between a British
prime minister and a Irish Catholic republican leader for 76 years.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is the political wing of the Irish Republican Army
(IRA), the largest nationalist paramilitary organization which has
resorted to violence to end the British rule of Northern Ireland
over the past 28 years, with 3,200 people being killed.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has drawn strong criticism from Northern Ireland's
Protestant majority, who fear the government may cave in to
republican demands for a united Ireland and an end to British rule
of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Blair would tell his critics he had a duty
to try to bring stability to Northern Ireland, just as he would
with any part of the United Kingdom that had been rocked by
violence.
</P>
<P>
Adams said on BBC radio Thursday morning that he wanted the
talks to produce peace for Northern Ireland, not just publicity
for his cause.
</P>
<P>
"The symbolism itself is important but it's the substance of the
meeting that is more important," said the Sinn Fein leader.
</P>
<P>
Adams will be accompanied by his chief negotiator, Mitchel
McLaughlin, and six other delegates. No handshake is expected at
the meeting which is expected to last about an hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
