<HEADLINE> PNA: Census in Jerusalem to Go Ahead Despite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) will go ahead with its census in East Jerusalem
despite a ban hastily adopted by Israeli Knesset (parliament),
said a cabinet minister of the PNA today.
</P>
<P>
But the PNA is to take census in the city in a different way
from that in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, PNA Minister for
Jerusalem Affairs Faisal Husseini told the press in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Census-takers will collect data of the Palestinians by fax,
rather than going door to door, said Husseini.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli reports, Palestinian census-takers may
pose as students to collect information for research.
</P>
<P>
Husseini said traditionally Arab East Jerusalem is regarded as
part of the Palestinian territories occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
He accused Israel of using repression to prevent the PNA from
implementing rights, including census, in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians claim East Jerusalem, captured by Israel in
the 1967 Mideast war, as their future capital of an independent
state.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Knesset passed a law in a marathon session late
Wednesday night to prohibit the Palestinians from carrying out
activities in East Jerusalem without "taking permission" from the
Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
The legislation also authorizes Israeli police to take actions
against the Palestinians who "violate" the legislation, to take
part in the census in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police were on the look-out in East Jerusalem for
Palestinian census-takers.
</P>
<P>
The census, the first of its kind since the formation of the
PNA, began Wednesday and went on smoothly in Gaza Strip and the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 staff and workers have been mobilized for the
census, which is to last a fortnight and the results will be
published next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
