<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Economic Conference Held in Beijing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A summary of the Chinese economy showed appropriately rapid
growth with low-level price rises in 1997, and showed a healthy
development trend towards "high growth and low inflation." The
market played increasingly important role in economic operations
and the allocation of resources. In addition, overall economic
structural adjustments showed signs of positive change, with more
marketable products and a better production/sales ratio.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China expanded economic and technical exchanges, with
an upsurge in foreign trade and a better international balance.
</P>
<P>
The conference indicated various noticeable contradictions and
problems in China's economic operations during the year and urged
that appropriate attention should be paid to finding solutions.
</P>
<P>
The list of problems included: a number of state-owned and
township enterprises operating in the red; the rising ranks of
laid-off workers; the imperfect legal system and poor supervision
of China's financial sector; the weak agricultural base; and the
deteriorating agricultural ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
In terms of economic work for 1998, the conference pointed to
the pressing need for the country to advance the moderization
drive towards the new century.
</P>
<P>
The conference proposed to meet goals by basing the general
principle of China's future economic work on upholding the great
banner of Deng Xiaoping Theory, fully implementing the guideline
formulated during the 15th Party Congress, promoting thorough
reforms related to China's economic system restructuring and
growth patterns, further enhancing the status of agriculture in
terms of the national economy, accelerating state enterprise
reform, continuing to readjust the economic structure,
strengthening and improving macroeconomic controls, opening
further, making a better arrangement for people's life and
realizing sustained, rapid and sound economic development, as well
as comprehensive social progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
