<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Economic Conference Held in Beijing (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The conference called for taking advantage of the current
favorable domestic and international situation to accelerate
structural readjustments to the economy, and stressed that the
roles of market and industrial policies should be strengthened in
order to improve the efficient use of resources.
</P>
<P>
The strategy to reinvigorate the nation by developing science
and education should be implemented with all due seriousness, and
full support should be given to pillar and hi-tech industries,
according to the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference called for current structural economic
readjustments to be combined with the accelerated development of
backward areas in central and western parts of the country. It
specifically called for developed areas in eastern China to
accelerate industrial upgrades, while relocating less advanced
industries to central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
Reform of the investment and financing systems should be
accelerated by separating the government from enterprises, and
establishing strict responsibility mechanisms to prevent financial
risks and redundant operations.
</P>
<P>
The conference pledged to further introduce and improve
macroeconomic controls in order to create a more favorable
environment for reform and development.
</P>
<P>
Based on the premise of optimizing the structure, China should
maintain a moderately rapid economic growth and appropriate growth
in investments, exports and consumption, keep a basic balance for
the macroeconomic volume, and avoid major fluctuations in economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The conference called for avoiding any factors which could
possibly spark inflation by deepening reform and using both
economic and legal means to establish a price regulation system to
maintain a relatively low inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
The relationship among foreign exchange, trade, investment and
debt must be properly handled to maintain an appropriate foreign
exchange reserve and ensure the balance of international payments.
</P>
<P>
The conference called for adherence to the moderately tight
monetary policy in order to achieve financial growth and
stability, and to promote sustained, rapid and healthy national
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The conference exhibited great concern about the financial
sector, urged accelerated and expanded financial reform needed to
establish a modern financial system. The supervisory role of the
central bank must be strengthened, while existing state-owned
commercial banks should be transformed into true commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The conference called for accelerated legislation to
standardize activities of the financial sector, safeguard order
and reduce risks in the sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Economic Conference Held in Beijing (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The conference urged that China open wider to the outside
world, enhance the level of opening, and further deepen the
restructuring of the foreign trade sector by optimizing the
structure of exports and imports in order to achieve basically
balanced foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
It also called for maintaining the steady growth of foreign
investment, and noted that more foreign funds should be earmarked
for agriculture, high technology, basic industry and
infrastructure. The financial sector should be gradually opened
step by step, according to the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference paid great attention to living standards of the
Chinese people and social stability in both urban and rural areas,
terming them as priority issues related to reform, development and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The conference urged all cities above the prefectural level to
establish their own systems to ensure the basic living standards
of local residents by the beginning of next year, while the
pension system for factory retirees and reemployment programs for
laid-off workers should be established at the earliest possible
date.
</P>
<P>
The conference called for the development of a multi-ownership
economy with a larger employment capacity.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials were urged to practice clean government and
provide assistance for poor families in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
The conference emphasized that economic work should be carried
out in line with economic law. Party organizations and governments
of all levels were urged to conscientiously safeguard the
authority of the central leadership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
