<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Assures Citizens of Keeping Linked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) will not change its
policy of linking the Hong Kong dollar with the U.S. dollar, Tung
Chee Hwa, chief executive of the HKSAR, said here today upon his
return from a duty visit to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"We don't need to change this policy because our economic
fundamentals are very good," Tung told reporters at the airport.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, Hong Kong's stock market is volatile recently due
to the impact of the financial turmoil in Asia, but I am confident
 that the repercussion will pass just like the big waves," Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks fell 602.19 points or 5.4 percent to close at
10,420.22 points this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
At the airport, Tung briefed the reporters on his first duty
visit to Beijing, saying that in Beijing, he called on President
Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng to report work.
</P>
<P>
He said he also met with vice premiers Zhu Rongji and Qian
Qichen as well as Liao Hui, director of the Hong Kong Macao
Affairs Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Tung said he explained to the leaders that in the past five and
half months after Hong Kong's return to the motherland, Hong
Kong's development in the fields of politics, economy and
livelihood is very well.
</P>
<P>
He also told the leaders that the operation of the SAR
government is very well, Hong Kong people continue to retain their
 original lifestyle and Hong Kong's economy is still expanding.
</P>
<P>
Tung said he took the opportunity to brief the leaders on the
reason of the Asian financial turmoil and its impact on Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He also reported to the leaders the measures of the SAR
government to deal with the financial turmoil and expressed his
confidence about Hong Kong's future, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that the leaders had spoken highly of the operation
of the SAR government and agreed with the SAR government's
measures to deal with the financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"The leaders introduced to me the direction of the economic
development of the country. They are confident about China's
economic development," Tung said, adding "I was encouraged by
their remarks."
</P>
<P>
The economic development of the country is very important for
the development of Hong Kong, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Since Hong Kong is now part of China, so it is right for the
leaders to show concerns about Hong Kong, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Not just the leadership, all across China, everybody is very
proud that Hong Kong is now part of China, Tung said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
