<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Troop Redeployment in West Bank Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy today demanded that the government make an urgent
decision on the further redeployment, warning failure to do so
will be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Israel Radio, Levy said anyone who thinks that
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu can go empty-handed into next
week's meeting with United States Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright is "naive."
</P>
<P>
A failure to understand the urgent need of such a decision will
lead to a "dangerous gamble," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that if without substantive committment by Netanyahu
to Albright, Israel will find itself in an impossible situation
of international isolation and will lose its most important
assests, its friendship with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is expected to hold a meeting next Thursday with
Albright in Paris to discuss Israel's decision on the second
further redeployment in the West Bank and Tel Aviv's position on
the permanent talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
During her two meetings with Netanyahu in Paris last week,
Albright reportedly pressed Israel to come out with a concrete and
more credible decision on the scope of further redeployment in
order to advance the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli officials have indicated that despite the
U.S. pressure, the Israeli government may not produce a final
decision on the percentage of the second redeployment before the
Netanyahu-Albright meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial panel charged with formulating plans for the
further redeployment and final-status talks, which is headed by
Netanyahu and includes Levy, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
and National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, has already
held three sessions but failed to reach consensus due to the
inner rift.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that while hard-liners Netanyahu and Sharon
favor creating expansive security zones along the Green Line
and Jordan Valley, moderates Levy and Mordechai insisted that
such zones can be much smaller.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial panel is to reconvene later today in another
effort to make progress before Netanyahu's scheduled meeting with
Albright next week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sharon denied an Israel Radio report earlier today
that he and Mordechai have allegedly agreed to set the scope of
the second redeployment at 13 percent, 10 percent come from Area C
under sole Israeli control and 3 percent from Area B under Israeli
and Palestinian joint control.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is reportedly demanding that Israel agree to pull out
troops from at least 12 percent of the West Bank in the second
redeployment, rather than the 6-8 percent originally proposed by
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Netanyahu held talks with a group of settler
leaders from the West Bank to discuss the government's plan to
carry out further redeployments.
</P>
<P>
The settler leaders demanded the government to ensure that the
Palestinian side fulfill its commitments to the signed agreements
before Israel takes actions to redeploy troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
