<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Telecom Active in Building Transpacific Cable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Hongkong Telecom, Hong
Kong's leading telecommunications services provider, will join
consortium to build the first undersea fiber-optic cable network
directly linking China and the United States, the company
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the company said that it has signed an
agreement with 13 leading telecommunications companies in the
Asia-Pacific Region on the one-billion-US-dollar project.
</P>
<P>
The 16,000-mile China-US cable network, one of the largest ever
constructed, will serve as a primary conduit for international
long-distance telecommunications traffic in the Pacific
Rim. Having a total of 80 gigabits per second, the system will be
able to carry one million phone calls simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Once the necessary permits are obtained, construction on the
cable network will begin and is expected to be completed by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Each of the 14 consortium members holds an equal stake, and
they will be jointly responsible for network oversight,
maintenance and administration.
</P>
<P>
The consortium is made up of China Telecom, Hongkong Telecom,
AT&AMP;T, MCI, Sprint, Kokusai Denshin Denwa (Japan), Nippon Telephone
&AMP; Telegraph (Japan), Korea Telecom, ITDC (Taiwan), SBC
Communications Inc., SingTel (Singapore), Telecom Malaysia,
Teleglobe, and Telstra (Australia).
</P>
<P>
With six submarine fiber-optic cable systems coming ashore in
Hong Kong and two cable linked with the inland areas of China,
Hong Kong now has more international cable landings than any other
cities in Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
