<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Summit Supports Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Islamic leaders have approved
six draft resolutions related to the Arab-Israeli conflict,
reaffirming support for Middle East peace process and its
principle of "land-for-peace."
</P>
<P>
All the 142 draft resolutions tabled at the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC) dealing with a wide range of issues both
within and outside the Muslim world have been approved.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic leaders supported the Palestinians'
"inalienable ... rights to return, to self-determination and to
the establishment of their independent state," according to the
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
They requested all the relevant U.N. resolutions, and
agreements signed by the Palestinians and Israel be implemented
and obligations and commitments fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
They strongly attacked Israel's hardline policies, pointing
finger at its attempt to Judaize Jerusalem and its continued
occupation of south Lebanon and Syria's Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are scheduled to approve a Tehran Declaration and
decide the venue for their next meeting before concluding the
three-day summit later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day eighth OIC summit opened here Tuesday with the
participation of all its members to seek solidarity and unity in
the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of Arab countries gave a hand to the
debt-ridden OIC at the summit, said an informed source. Saudi
Arabia has offered the organization 10 million U.S. dollars, while
Qatar and Kuwait have each pledged 3 million, Iran 1 million, and
Egypt half a million.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old, 55-membered Islamic body now has a debt of 15
million U.S. dollars due to its low budgets and difficulty to
collect financing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair to Meet Sinn Fein Leader in Downing Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair will hold a historic meeting with Sinn Fein leader Gerry
Adams in Downing Street later Thursday, the first such meeting
over the past 76 years.
</P>
<P>
Blair is expected to make clear to Adams that if Sinn Fein
turns its back on the Mitchell Principles, his party will be
kicked out of the multi-party peace talks. The principles call for
all parties involved in the talks to renounce violence.
</P>
<P>
In an article published on Thursday's Sun newspaper, Blair said
he would warn Sinn Fein that "if you return to violence, there
will be no place for you at the negotiation table."
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is the political wing of the Irish Republican Army
(IRA), the largest nationalist paramilitary organization in
Northern Ireland, which has been fighting to end the British rule
of the divided province over the past 28 years.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview with GMTV earlier in the day, Adams
said that his goals at the meeting were clear: a lasting peace in
Northern Ireland and a commitment from Blair that he would coax
pro-British Protestant Unionists towards a deal for the province.
</P>
<P>
"We're not there to make publicity. We're there to make peace,"
Adams said.
</P>
<P>
Blair promised to meet Adams to reward Sinn Fein for a
five-month-old IRA truce that has won the party a seat at
political negotiations on Northern Ireland's future. But it has
drawn widespread criticism from Northern Ireland's pro-British
Protestant community.
</P>
<P>
A senior Ulster Unionist Party official, Reg Empey, said the
meeting should be called off.
</P>
<P>
"We warned him (the prime minister) it was going to be a
high-risk strategy because we do not believe the Republican
movement is committed to exclusively peaceful means yet." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sensitive Index on BSE Market Loses 18.19 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 11 (Xinhua)-- The sensitive index on the
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market today lost 18.19 points to
close at 3,329.14 as against Wednesday's close of 3,347.33.
</P>
<P>
The national index also fell by 8.20 points to 1,448.94 from
the previous close of 1,457.14.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the U.S. dollar index were quoted marginally
lower at 324.86 and 137.20 compared with the previous closes of
327.59 and 139.67 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The sensitive index pierced through the 3,319 support level and
dropped below the 3,300-mark at 3,247.63 around mid-session,
reflecting a setback in share prices on the BSE market today on
continued selling pressure from foreign institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
Apart from foreign institutional investors who sold heavily,
bear operators were also reported to have sold heavily. The market
has been witnessing a bear phase since the last couple of weeks
and the sensitive index has lost more than 231 points during the
current month.
</P>
<P>
Market sources said that investors were keeping away from the
market in the absence of any clear indication about which party
will form the new government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
