<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surveys Show Chinese College Students Know More About HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- About 93 percent of Chinese
college students know that people sharing intravenous injection
needles or having sex without using condoms are possibly infected
by human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), according to a survey.
</P>
<P>
Anti-AIDS experts quoted the survey results as saying that
Chinese students have understood HIV/AIDS better as a
result of educational programs provided by schools and social
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The survey was made among some 3,000 college and university
students by a sociological research institute under the
Beijing-based People's University this April. Its results were
published at an on-going symposium on AIDS
(acquired immunodeficiency syndrome) in China.
</P>
<P>
The survey found 60 percent of the students know HIV could be
transmitted through blood transfusion. And 75 percent said they
need to know more about the disease.
</P>
<P>
Another survey, conducted in Beijing, Shanghai and six other
major cities, found nearly all college students know AIDS is an
infectious disease, and only nine percent of them wrongly think
AIDS is curable.
</P>
<P>
The experts attending the symposium said it is very important
to help college students obtain more HIV/AIDS knowledge.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission, the country's highest
educational authority, has ordered colleges and universities to
add courses about HIV/AIDS and sexually transmitted diseases
(STDs), said Zhang Xin, a SEC official in charge of health
education.
</P>
<P>
"We've asked the schools to carry out sex education more widely
among students in order to prevent HIV/AIDS from invading into the
campus," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fund Management Code Aimed at Investor Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Securities and
Futures Commission (SFC) today issued a revised edition of the
Code on Unit Trusts and Mutual Funds, a regulatory document
guiding the fund management industry and protecting investors.
</P>
<P>
This is the third edition of the Code, which has been amended
on a regular basis since 1990 in response to market development.
</P>
<P>
Latest revisions include new requirement that trustees be
subject to supervision, new provision to clarify policy on pricing
errors and many others.
</P>
<P>
"The underlying spirit of the Code continues to be core
standards for investor protection, especially the appropriate
supervision of all parties, whether in Hong Kong or overseas,"
said Deborah Glass, senior director of the SFC's investment
products division.
</P>
<P>
She added: "In keeping with Hong Kong's open market policies,
the Code not only remains open to properly regulated overseas
funds, but also expands the list of overseas countries to give
Hong Kong investors even greater choice."  
</P>
</TEXT>
