<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Signs Tax Reform Bill Into Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today signed into law the long-delayed Comprehensive Tax
Reform Package (CTRP), paving the way for the country to exit from
the supervision of the International Monetary Program (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The bill, which will significantly improve the government's
fiscal position, is a vital requirement for the country's planned
exit from 35 years of economic supervision by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The country was supposed to graduate from the last IMF
supervision program in June this year, but the graduation was
delayed due to the lower house's failure to pass the corporate and
individual income tax bill, the third and last part of the CTRP.
</P>
<P>
The income tax reform bill was finally ratified by both the
lower house and the upper house Monday after the lower house
agreed to the Senate's version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
With the signing of the tax reform bill, the country is
expected to graduate from the IMF at the end of this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
