<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Unlikely to Meet Cotton Production Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is unlikely to meet
the cotton production target of 10 million bales this year as the
main export crop of the country was substantially damaged by
natural calamity, officials said today.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan will produce about 9 to 9.2 million bales of cotton
this year (1997-98) as the crop was damaged by heavy rains, hail
and wind storms, according to the officials at Central Cotton
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Punjab province, which was expected to produce 8.4 million
bales of cotton, is likely to produce only about 7.1 million to
7.3 million bales while Sindh province will produce 1.9 million,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
An increase in the sugarcane price also diverted the growers
from sowing cotton, which resulted in an 8 percent decrease in
cotton growing area in the country, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siemens Heading for Record Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Europe's biggest electrical
engineering group Siemens said Thursday it expected net profits in
the current business year to hit a record of three to four billion
marks.
</P>
<P>
The German firm attributed the prospects to its acquisition of
the fossil-fuel electricity-generating plants of Westinghouse of
the United States and the takeover of Electrowatt of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Siemens saw its net profits rising to 2.61 billion marks (1.5
billion U.S. dollars) in the past 1996/97 business year ending
September 30, up five percent from a year before.
</P>
<P>
The results were achieved on sales of 106.9 billion marks, an
increase of 14 percent, with overseas sales growing to 70.6
billion marks, or about 66 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Chief executive Heinrich von Pierer told reporters in Munich
that orders rose 12 percent in the last business year to 113.1
billion marks, while investment was up 24 percent to 9.8 billion
marks.
</P>
<P>
He said orders were heading for between 115 billion and 120
billion marks this year and that investment would top 10 billion
marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
