<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland, China Win at World Weightlifting Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIANG MAI, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Andrzej Cogfalik claimed
the first gold medal for Poland at the World Weightlifting
Championships for 15 years here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Polish strongman took the title in the 83kg category with
172.5 kilograms in the snatch and 380kg in the total. But he had
to be content with the bronze medal in the clean and jerk with a
lift of 207.5kg.
</P>
<P>
Chinese hercules Zhang Yong, world record holder for clean and
jerk, won China's eighteenth gold of the championships with a lift
of 207.5kg. Cofalik's Polish teammate Krzystof Siemion took the
silver.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Dursun Sevinc took silver in the total category with
375kg and bronze in the snatch with 170kg, while Russian Yuri
Miskovetz won the snatch silver with 172.5kg.
</P>
<P>
In the women's event, China's Xiang Fenglan set three women's
world records in the 70kg class.
</P>
<P>
Xiang added a half kilo to the previous bests when she snatched
105.5kg and jerked 130.5kg -- both with only her second attempt.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old, in her first world championships, had not
increased her lifts by the statutory 2.5kg for the attempts to
count for the competition total but her first attempts of 105kg
and 130kg were enough to count for a world record total of 235kg.
</P>
<P>
Chinese lifters have now broken seven records at the world
championships and won 17 gold medals, which, unlike the Olympics,
are awarded for each event -- snatch, jerk and total.
</P>
<P>
Huang Hsi-Li of Chinese Taipei won the jerk bronze and overall
silver while Hungary's Ilona Danko, the snatch silver medallist,
was the overall bronze medallist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
