<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Welcomes Agreement at Kyoto Climate Change Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- France on Thursday welcomed the
agreement in Kyoto, Japan, on an average 5.2 percent cut in major
industrial countries' emissions of greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
French Minister of Environment Dominique Voynet said the
agreement reached earlier in the day at the United Nations climate
change conference was "more than honorable" for Europe and France.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the United States and Japan finally accepted "what
they rejected for several months," Voynet hailed the solidarity by
European Union (EU) countries in negotiations with the two nations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement "marks a considerable new progress for the
protection of global environment," she was quoted as saying by the
Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Brice Lalonde, president of the French non-government group
Generation Ecologie, said the agreement "will mark a date in the
history of the protection of environment."
</P>
<P>
Greenhouse gases are group of chemicals, mainly carbon dioxide,
released largely as the result of industrial activities, such as
the burning of fossil fuels, including oil and coal.
</P>
<P>
They could prevent the solar radiation from reflecting back
into space, thus trapping the heat within the Earth's atmosphere
and causing what is called "greenhouse effect."
</P>
<P>
In recent years, scientists have been providing more convincing
evidences to pinpoint greenhouse gases behind what is believed to
be an ongoing potentially devastating "global warming" trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Cut 200 Million U.S. Dollars in Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian Armed
Forces will cut its expenditure by 700 million ringgit (200
million U.S. dollars) and will suspend all inter-state troops
movements, it was officially announced today.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces would also not fill vacancies created by
compulsory and optional retirement of personnel, Malaysian
national news agency Bernama quoted Malaysian Defense Minister
Syed Hamid Albar as saying today after a function here.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that new housing projects for military
personnel would also be deferred but projects that already started
would be completed.
</P>
<P>
He said the cost-cutting measures were in tandem with measures
taken by the Federal Government to deal with the economic problems
caused by the depreciation of the ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government recently announced an 18 percent
expenditure cut for 1998 and a 10 percent pay cut for ministers
and deputy ministers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
