<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Tourist Arrivals to Increase in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Cyprus
for 1997 are expected to increase by 5 percent compared with that
of last year, an official from Cyprus Tourism Organization (CTO)
has said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Mail today quoted the unidentified CTO official as
saying that "our estimates are pointing to a 5 percent rise of
tourist arrivals by the end of 1997, to an overall arrivals figure
of 2.05 million tourists."
</P>
<P>
According to the official, foreign visitors to Cyprus in
October reached 224,371, compared to 194,500 in October
1996. British tourists accounted for nearly 40 percent of the
October 1997 arrivals, followed by Germany with 14.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures were regarded as good news for the island, which is
heavily dependent on tourism.
</P>
<P>
The income of tourism industry accounts for nearly 20 percent
of the island's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The figures also backed the positive picture painted
Wednesday by Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou, who
forecast a 2.5 percent GDP growth this year and 4 percent
growth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Christodoulou said the number of
tourists coming to the island rose 8 percent year-on-year for
May-October period this year.
</P>
<P>
The paper also quoted bankers and economists as saying that
the rise in tourist arrivals in 1997 was largely due to the
Cyprus pound's depreciation against the British pound. More than
a third of the tourists who visited Cyprus are British.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
