<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Li Ruihuan Meets NZ Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- China would like to
strengthen its cooperation with all countries in the world
including New Zealand to make contributions to the sustainable
development of the mankind, Chinese leader Li Ruihuan said here
today.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny
Shipley, Li Ruihuan, chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, said that the
Chinese government has made the strategy of sustainable
development as the country's fundamental state policy, and will
positively implement it.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Li, who arrived here this morning on a
four-day visit to the country, extended his congratulation to
Shipley for taking the prime minister' office and the leadership
of the National Party.
</P>
<P>
He also conveyed to Shipley the cordial regards and
congratulations of Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li
Peng, and welcome her to visit China at her convenience.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said that Li is the first distinguished visitor she has
greeted after she swore in as prime minister on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I see this as a good omen, and a symbol of the importance of
China for New Zealand," she said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that in the 25 years after the two countries
established diplomatic ties in 1972, the constant strengthening of
the cooperation between the two countries has laid solid
foundation for the bilateral friendly cooperative ties between
China and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her conviction that this kind of bilateral
relations will be pushed into a new stage.
</P>
<P>
Li told Shipley that China has noted with pleasure that since
the coalition government of New Zealand came to office last year,
it had on many occasions indicated that it attaches importance to
relations with China and that it continues to pursue a "one China"
policy and opposes the containment of China.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand government took the lead in announcing that it
would send Deputy Prime Minister Winston Peters to attend all the
activities for the return of Hong Kong to China, including the
swearing-in ceremony of the Provisional Legislative Council of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
China and New Zealand concluded a bilateral market access
agreement in August this year in the context of China's entry into
the World Trade Organization, making New Zealand the first
Western country to have such an agreement with China.
</P>
<P>
Li continued to say that two-way trade between China and New
Zealand has enjoyed rapid development, which has become a
significant feature in the two countries' bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
There are broad prospects for the mutually beneficial
cooperation between the two countries, Li said, as the rapid
development of China's economy makes it a market with great
potential and New Zealand has advantages in agriculture, forestry
and animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
Li arrived here this morning from Christchurch, the largest
city in South Island of New Zealand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
