<HEADLINE> Beijing to Open wider to World, Mayor Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will further open its
gate to the world so as to attract quality overseas-funded
programs to the city, Mayor Jia Qinglin said here today.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Xinhua reporters before the opening of the
Eighth Beijing Municipal Congress of the Communist Party of China
(CPC), Jia, who is also secretary of the CPC Beijing Municipal
Committee, said that in the past five years, Beijing has actually
used overseas investments of 9 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Now, 138 of the 500 largest transnational corporations in the
world have come to Beijing to do business, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jia, also member of the Political Bureau of the CPC's Central
Committee, pointed out that promoting economic development will
further improve Beijing's functions as capital of China.
</P>
<P>
He said that foreign investors are expected to put their funds
to the development of infrastructural facilities, new and high
technology and comprehensive application of energy.
</P>
<P>
He said that Beijing should accelerate economic development so
as to lay substantial foundation for realizing the capital's
functions as the national political and cultural center.
</P>
<P>
He said that he expects Beijing to see a sustained economic
growth in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
During the Eighth Five-Year Plan Period (1991-95), Beijing's
annual economic growth rate was 12 percent. This year the rate
will be 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the next few years, the growth rate of Beijing
will be 9 percent while the inflation rate under 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
He noted that to realize the goals, Beijing should give full
play to its advantages, boost the development of high and
new technology, and build a high-efficient and open economy with
optimized industrial set-ups.
</P>
<P>
Jia said that Beijing is expected to make use of its scientific
and technological advantages to promote economic development.
There are about 100 universities and institutions run by the State
with more than 1.1 million scholars and scientists.
</P>
<P>
He said that of the high and new technology-oriented
industries, development priority should go to industries like
electronics information, biological engineering, new medicines,
and new materials.
</P>
<P>
Jia also outlined four sectors which will be stressed in
Beijing in the next five years: service trade with focus on
commerce, finance, insurance, communications, cultural
entertainment, sports and tourism; modern agriculture including
the export-oriented farming services, ecological agriculture, rare
animal and plants raising and breeding, and flower producing; key
industries like electronics, automobiles and machinery; and civil
housing industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
