<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rabbani Demands Restoration of Afghan Seat in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Afghan President Burhanuddin
Rabbani said today that he does not accept the decision to leave
the Afghan seat vacant in the three-day eighth Islamic summit
being held here.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua at the summit hall, he
said that his government would not accept the decision because
it has not been made by the foreign ministers' meeting or the
summit, but "by a few members in a very hurried way" before the
summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
He stated that his government is recognized by the
international community and therefore should be recognized by the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the OIC foreign ministers meeting in Jakarta,
Indonesia, in 1996 recognized his government as a true
representative of Afghanistan which had the right to occupy the
seat of the organization. But to his regret, the decision had
been changed by some members.
</P>
<P>
He said that leaders attending the current meeting of the OIC
summit should reverse the decision and restore the rights to his
government.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in order to solve the Afghan issue, foreign
interference should be stopped first, the war in his country
should come to an end and negotiations between different factions
should start in a peaceful atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
As to the future political set-up of Afghanistan, he said
that it should be decided by the whole people of Afghanistan
through a general election or Loya Jirgah (national assembly).
</P>
<P>
On the peace efforts by Iran and Pakistan, Rabbani said,
"Iranian and Pakistani officials met Wednesday to seek a way out
of the Afghan crisis, and they had invited my government to join
in the discussions. There is no obstacle for our
participation." However, he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani said that his government is ready to negotiate with
the Taliban regime in Kabul to find a peaceful solution to the
Afghan issue. "However, if the Taliban forces do not accept
peace, then we have to be ready for war and recapture the
capital city of Kabul," he added.
</P>
<P>
He denied reports that Iran had provided military or
financial aid to his government, but saying that he is grateful
to Iranian humanitarian aid to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the United Nations and the international
community at large to help Afghanistan end the foreign
intervention and bring back peace to the landlocked nation.
</P>
<P>
Guerilla forces took over Kabul in April 1992, and Rabbani,
leader of Jamiat-e-Islami, was empowered as head of the state by
groups of the guerilla forces.
</P>
<P>
After years of battle for control of Kabul, Taliban forces
emerged in 1994 and defeated the government forces in 1996 by
capturing the capital. Now the Taliban government is only
recognized by Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and
Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profits of State-Owned Enterprises Up (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The economic returns of
state-owned enterprises was in a steady revival in the third
quarter of this year, with their losses shrinking significantly
following good performance in the January-June period.
</P>
<P>
The statement is contained in an official report jointly issued
today by the State Statistics Bureau, the Ministry of Finance and
the State Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
During the first three quarters this year, all the 67,400
state-owned enterprises made pre-tax profits totaling 199.66
billion yuan, up 10.31 percent from the same period in 1996. Their
post-tax profits reached 22.56 billion yuan, up 67.74 percent on
an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
The loss of the enterprises running in the red amounted to 63.5
billion yuan, of which the proportion in pre-tax profits
decreased to 31.8 percent, compared to 34.3 percent in the same
period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the mean time, the comprehensive index for enterprise
economic returns grew by 2.59 percentage points on an annual
basis, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In wake of a net loss of 1.5 billion yuan in the first quarter
this year, the state-owned sector realized a rebound in profit in
the second quarter, with its net profits hitting 13.59 billion
yuan, up 57.86 percent an an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth rate was impeded by both the hot weather
and sluggish market in the third quarter, with the pre-tax
profits amounting to 68.67 billion yuan, up 4.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the profit gap between the enterprises run
by the central government and those run by local governments has
further widened, because the comparatively larger production scale
and capital ensured an advantageous position for central
government-owned enterprises in the increasingly fierce market
competition.
</P>
<P>
In the July-September period, the 3,582 central
government-owned enterprises made net profits totaling 11.38
billion yuan, up 32.54 percent, while enterprises run by local
governments incurred losses reaching 914 million yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profits of State-Owned Enterprises Up (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The net profits of central government-owned enterprises
amounted to 31 billion yuan during the first three quarters, up
43.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the lossed of other state enterprises
increased by 252 million yuan over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the central government's statistics over 30
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions except Tibet, the
performance of enterprises in most regions has improved since the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Among the 14 regions which reported profits in the third quarter,
Beijing, Yunnan, Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Fujian, Hubei, Guangdong and
Sichuan increased their profits by more than 30 percent over the
same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The losses of the state enterprises in Tianjin, Ningxia,
Xinjiang, Guizhou and Gansu decreased by more than one fifth.
</P>
<P>
Benefitting from the improved market environment and trend
toward enterprise merger, large and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises, whose number accounts for 22 percent of the total of
the state sector, took the lead in the enterprise revival
and generated 94.8 percent of the profits and taxes of the state
sector in the January-September period.
</P>
<P>
However, the losses of small enterprises are still large,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Though the state-owned sector achieved a significant increase
in profits during the January-September period, the basis for the
revival, which refers to the profits of state-owned enterprises in
1996, is rather weak, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
