<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Clubs Allowed to Market European Cup Home Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- German federal supreme court
ruled in Karlsruhe on Thursday that the country's soccer clubs can
freely market the broadcast rights to home games in two European
competitions, the UEFA Cup and the Cup Winners' Cup.
</P>
<P>
The court upheld a 1993 ruling by the federal Cartel Office
breaking the German soccer federation's monopoly on the TV rights,
which the anti-trust agency viewed as a way to drive up prices.
</P>
<P>
A Berlin administrative court had also ruled against the
federation.
</P>
<P>
The federal court said the federation had ``no rights'' to
marketing the games. It did not specify whether European soccer's
governing body, UEFA, was entitled to share in the clubs'
marketing rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
