<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> VAl D'Isere Downhill Piste Named After Two Local Greats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Val d'Isere downhill piste
has been named after the name of the two of the most famous skiers
bred in the Savoie village, Henri Oreiller and Jean-Claude Killy.
</P>
<P>
The 3,400 meter-long piste was thus named the "OK" piste in
1966 to honour Oreiller, the men's 1948 Olympic champion, and
Killy, who completed a clean sweep of Olympic medals in 1968.
</P>
<P>
The piste has become a classic of the World Cup circuit with 26
men's and 21 women's World Cup downhills held on it since 1969.
</P>
<P>
It is an extension of the La Daille piste which had hosted the
Criterium de la Premiere Neige (Criterium of the first snow) since
1956.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Francois Bonlieu won the first two competitive
downhills held in the piste. 
</P>
</TEXT>
