<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25th Anniversary of Sino-New Zealand Ties Marked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Senior Chinese and New
Zealand Leaders called for efforts to strengthen the Sino-New
Zealand bilateral ties here today at a reception held to mark the
25th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic ties between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At the reception, hosted by New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny
Shipley, Li Ruihuan, visiting chairman of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference National Committee, hailed the
all-round development of the Sino-New Zealand relations over the
past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
"We may learn something useful from this 25-year history," Li
said, "Countries, in their contact with one another, should hold
each other in respect, respect each other's specific national
conditions and historical traditions, and respect the will and
political choice of each other's peoples."
</P>
<P>
"Only by respecting others can one be respected," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that countries should also equitably and fairly handle
the ties between their respective interests and seek common
development on the basis of equality, mutual benefit,
complementarity and reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
"Only by accommodating the interests of others can one's own
interests be guaranteed," Li said.
</P>
<P>
He continued to say that countries should deepen their
knowledge about each other and reach understandings with each
other as common ground is built on constant communication.
</P>
<P>
"Countries should follow the principle of seeking common ground
while putting aside differences, acknowledge the diversity of the
world, acknowledge the differences among the countries in terms of
economic interests, cultural traditions and value judgment, and
explore common interests and universally applicable principles
from those differences by treating each other with sincerity,
equality and politeness," Li noted.
</P>
<P>
He told the reception that only by seeking common ground while
putting aside differences can the common ground be steadily
expanded and the differences steadily reduced.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that as long as our two sides handle matters in
such a spirit, the friendly and cooperative relations between us
will bear even richer fruits in the next 25 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Located in the Asia-Pacific region, both China and New Zealand
are members of Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation and ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) Regional Forum and share
broad common ground in safeguarding regional peace and promoting
regional economic development, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the two economies of China and New Zealand, with
their distinctive features, are highly complementary.
</P>
<P>
"We should, in a positive and pragmatic attitude, tap into and
utilize the Sino-New Zealand economic potentials so as to inject
fresh vitality into our respective economic growth," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said that after the development of 25 years, the
bilateral relations now rest on solid foundations.
</P>
<P>
"We have an active dialogue," she said. "Our two way trade and
investment is substantial, and still growing. And we have built
bridges of friendship and understanding."
</P>
<P>
She noted that over the past 25 years, the New Zealand has come
to look to the Asia-Pacific community as the place where it
belongs, and its dialogue with China is growing.
</P>
<P>
"Looking to the future, I believe we are at the threshold of a
new phase in our relationship," she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
