<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief on Peace Process, OIC, Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan said here today that he hoped the U.N. can
act as a coordinator in pushing forward the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference this afternoon, Annan said
that the U.N. has adopted a series of resolutions on the
regional conflict and that he hoped those resolutions can be
implemented by both the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
He asked the two sides to regard the U.N. as a peace
coordinator. Otherwise, he said, too many coordinators could
make things more complicated.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here Monday to attend the eighth summit of
the Organization of the Islamic Conference and then pay a visit
to Iran.
</P>
<P>
He called the Islamic summit a "significant" event with the
participation of more than 30 presidents, vice-presidents, crown
prices and prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a proposal made by Iran's supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei on the Islamic world's representation in
the U.N. Security Council, Annan said the reform of the U.N. can
only be decided by all members of the world body.
</P>
<P>
In an opening speech at the summit, Khamenei said the OIC
should become a sixth permanent member of the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he has raised a set of reform-oriented programs in
order to make the U.N. more effective and responsive to world
crises.
</P>
<P>
He envisioned better cooperative relationship between the OIC
and the U.N. in the future, in addition to their past good
coordinations on the issues of Somalia and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Fielding questions from reporters, Annan said the
U.N. sanctions against Iraq is not directed at punishing the
Iraqi people, and the "oil-for-food" deal between the U.N. and
Iraq itself spells out the fact that the U.N. is aimed at
alleviating the sufferings and crises of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
On the Afghan issue, he said that there will be no military
solution to the conflict, and that it can only be settled
through dialogue and negotiations among all factions and forces.
</P>
<P>
He urged neighboring countries to exercise an arms embargo on
Afghanistan to enable military conflicts there to peter off
pending a complete solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
