<HEADLINE> No-confidence Motion Against Hashimoto Cabinet Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of
Representatives, the lower house, Thursday rejected a
no-confidence motion tabled by opposition camp against Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The motion, the first against Hashimoto's cabinet since he took
office in January 1996, was voted down by 268 to 219 at a lower
house plenary session.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition New Frontier Party (NFP) tabled the motion
accusing the cabinet of failing to take appropriate economic measures
and leaving the economy on the verge of crisis.
</P>
<P>
Members of the NFP and other opposition parties such as the
Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ), the Japanese Communist Party (JCP)
and the Taiyo Party voted for the motion.
</P>
<P>
Members of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), which
enjoys a majority in the 500-seat lower house, and its two non
cabinet allies, the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New Party
Sakigake, voted against the motion.
</P>
<P>
Following a series of failures of Japan's financial
institutions such as the Yamaichi Securities Co, public support
rate for Hashimoto's cabinet have dropped due to voters'
disappointment with economic measures and Hashimoto's perceived
lack of leadership, according to recent opinion polls conducted by
Japanese media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
