<HEADLINE> Two Lots Sold for 44 Million US Dollars at HK Land Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Two government lots were
sold for a total of 343 million HK dollars (44 million U.S.
dollars) at a public auction this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Bidding involved many small and medium-sized property
developers as both lots, located in the "New Territories", are
small-sized.
</P>
<P>
The first lot, with an area of 2,293 square meters, was sold to
Winfield Investment Ltd. for 285 million HK dollars (37 million
U.S. dollars), with bidding starting at 170 million HK dollars (22
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The developer has to complete a gross floor area of not less
than 8,400 square meters on or before June 30, 2001. The lot is
intended for non-industrial purposes excluding godown, petrol
filling station, hotel and service apartments.
</P>
<P>
The second lot, with an area of 1,950 square meters, was bought
by Kisland Investment Ltd. for 58 million HK dollars (7 million
U.S. dollars), with bidding opened at 25 million HK dollars (3
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The developer has to complete a gross floor area of not less
than 1,170 square meters on or before December 31, 2000. The lot
is designated for private residential uses excluding service
apartments.
</P>
<P>
The auction was held by the Lands Department and conducted by
Government Land Agent Ian MacNaughton.  
</P>
