<HEADLINE> Downer Sees Good Results in China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer described his current visit to China as "a
complete success" which has led to great progress in bilateral
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held in the Australian Embassy
here today, Downer expressed great confidence with the current
status of bilateral relations with China.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the two sides fully appreciate the long and
successful relationship over the past 25 years since the two
nations forged diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Australia fully supports China's entry into
the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
"We are in the process of negotiating the terms for China's
entry into the World Trade Organization, and very hopeful that
negotiations between relevant countries and China will reach a
successful conclusion in the near future," according to Downer.
</P>
<P>
"I'm extremely pleased that China is preparing to approve the
business license for an Australian insurance company. In addition,
I'm pleased that the Chinese Government has decided to approve a
business license for a second Australian insurance company in the
near future," said Downer.
</P>
<P>
He said the approval of a license for a law firm will increase
the number of Australian companies operating in China to three.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Chinese government's recent designation of
Australia as an approved tourist destination represents an
important development in bilateral economic and trade
cooperation. He said the approval will benefit Australia's
economic and tourism sectors during a period in which a number of
southeast Asian countries face financial turmoil and the number of
tourists from the said countries will most likely diminish.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Tourism Forecast Council of Australia projects
that the number of Chinese tourists visiting the country will grow
from 53,000 in 1996 to 139,000 in 2001, and even further to over
300,000 by 2003.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe we will do even better than that," said Downer.
</P>
<P>
"I'm absolutely delighted with the status of our bilateral
relations which continue to gain even greater strength. The
momentum of our relationship is quite obvious and we sincerely
hope to accelerate same," according to Downer.
</P>
<P>
The Australian leader departed Beijing today for northwest
China's Xi'an to continue his three-day visit.  
</P>
