<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Ceremony On 60th Anniversary Of Nanjing Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A forum was held in Beijing
today to mark the 60th anniversary of the Nanjing Massacre of
civilians by Japanese troops.
</P>
<P>
In December 1937, the Japanese intruding troops seized Nanjing,
the Chinese capital at that time, and slaughtered 300,000
civilians and unarmed soldiers within a six-week time period. The
event was called "a dark page in modern human civilization" by
historians.
</P>
<P>
Japan's aggression against China constituted part of its move
toward destinations in Southeast Asia and elsewhere. Nanjing was
targeted after the invaders defeated Chinese troops in Beijing and
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Scholars and officials present today said that attempts by the
Japanese right wingers to cover over the truth of the massacre
must be exposed, and that the Chinese must remember the event to
promote patriotism. China has adequate materials to prove that the
massacre actually took place.
</P>
<P>
The forum was held by the Chinese Association for the History
of the War of Resistance against Japanese Aggression and several
other organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's External Trade Up in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's re-exports and
imports both jumped by 11 percent in October 1997 over a year
earlier, according to the latest government statistics.
</P>
<P>
Re-exports reached 122.9 billion HK dollars (15.7 billion US
dollars) in October this year, and imports hit 152.9 billion HK
dollars (19.6 billion US dollars), the Census and Statistics
Department said here today.
</P>
<P>
Domestic exports in October also went up by 3.1 percent to 20
billion HK dollars (2.6 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the first ten months this year, re-exports rose by 4.6
percent over the same period of 1996 to 1,032.2 billion HK dollars
(132 billion US dollars), imports gained 5.6 percent to 1,344.3
billion HK dollars (172 billion US dollars), while domestic
exports edged up 0.7 percent to 174.7 billion HK dollars (22
billion US dollars).  
</P>
