<HEADLINE> China To Commemorate Human Rights Declaration's Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- China's Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Tang Guoqiang said today that plans for marking the 50th
anniversary of the Universal Declaration on Human Rights are now
under discussion by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
China also supports the UN to launch activities in
commemoration of the occasion, Tang said. The declaration was
passed on December 10, 1948 by the UN General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that the basic principles enshrined in the
declaration have great significance for the development and
progress of mankind, and that it is an important document,
especially in its recognization of economic, social, and cultural
rights for the first time in history, and its impact on the
overall promotion and protection of human rights.
</P>
<P>
He said that China regards the commemoration as an opportunity
to sum up past experiences and lessons on the promotion and
protection of human rights, to look to the future, and to increase
co-operation among nations.
</P>
<P>
And, the Chinese government has had some achievements in
promoting and protecting human rights in an all-round manner, Tang
said. By working with its specific situation, China has taken the
promotion of the rights of the people's subsistence and
development as its primary task, and the economic, social and
cultural rights of the Chinese people have improved
considerablely, he said. On such basis, the Chinese government
has signed the International Convenant on Economic, Social and
Cultural Rights.
</P>
<P>
In the area of protecting the citizens' civil and political
rights, the Chinese government has passed many important laws and
continually strengthened its socialist democracy, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that, while emphasizing human rights within the
nation, China has actively engaged in dialogues and communications
with other countries, on the basis of equality and mutual respect,
to increase international co-operation in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
