<HEADLINE> Ugandan People Want More Local Language Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan residents asked for
another newspaper in local language, The Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
Remegious Kataratambi, a local council vice chairman in Kabale
district, asked The Monitor to introduce a sister paper in local
language for south-western Ugandans to promote development of
local culture.
</P>
<P>
Development cannot be achieved without well informed people,
Kataratambi said.
</P>
<P>
Karebi (monitor in local language in south-western Uganda)
weekly should be introduced in Kabale, Rukungiri and Ntungamo
districts, he added.
</P>
<P>
Local people can expand their knowledge on national issues
through the local language newspaper, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Monitor is an English daily. There are two English dailies
in Uganda. The other one is The New Vision.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has four main ethnic groups -- Gandas, Nilotics,
Hamid-Nilotics and Sudanics. Each ethnic group has its own
languge. A person from an ethnic group has dificulties to
communicate with other people from other ethnic groups if not
trained.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has at least seven local language newspapers now.
</P>
<P>
Local language education has attracted more attention among
Ugandans in the wake of development in the country in recent
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
