<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Wants to Solve Problems with Iran: Ramadan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha
Yassin Ramadan, who is attending the eighth Islamic summit here,
said today that he will stay after the meeting to sort out
problems between his country and Iran with Iranian officials.
</P>
<P>
"We just can not allow problems between our two countries to
linger on unresolved," Ramadan told Xinhua on the fringe of the
summit attended by Muslim countries across the world.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Iran fought a protracted war during 1980-88, causing
an estimated one million casualties on both sides, devastating
damages to their economies and untold human sufferings to the two
peoples.
</P>
<P>
They resumed diplomatic relations in October, 1990, soon
after the breakout of the Gulf crisis triggered by Baghdad's
invasion of Kuwait. But problems left over from that war,
including the issues of POWs (prisoners of war), war reparations
and Iraqi aircraft, which flew to Iran to escape allied attacks
during the Gulf War, stand in the way to improved relations.
</P>
<P>
"We hope this meeting can create a good opportunity for the
two sides to improve relations, which is beneficial to both,"
Ramadan said, adding Iraq looks forward to better ties with the
old rival.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan admitted there are 62 Iranians currently detained in
Iraq, far fewer than the 15,000 claimed by Tehran. Several days
ahead of the summit, Iran released 498 Iraqi POWs and Iraq
reciprocated by freeing two Iranians.
</P>
<P>
This summit of the Organization of the Islamic Conference which
opened here Tuesday and will end today, the largest such event
in Iran after the Islamic revolution in 1979, seems to have
succeeded in rallying Islamic leaders whatever their differences.
</P>
<P>
It highlighted the conflicts between Arabs and Israel at a
time when the Likud government's tough policies virtually sent
the Middle East peace process to a dead end. It also addressed
Turkey's repeated incursions into northern Iraq, saying Iraq's
sovereignty and territorial integrity should be respected.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan said Turkey is abetted by the United States in a bid
to make use of Iraq's present difficulties. "What Turkey does
will only bring serious consequences, not to Iraq, but to Turkey
itself," he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey denied it wanted to invade Iraq, arguing its troops'
entry into northern Iraq was to eliminate its outlawed Kurdish
militants, who use the area as a shelter and springboard for
attacks on targets inside Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel withdrew from the summit
Wednesday, one day ahead of schedule, to avoid facing growing
criticism of his country's ties with Israel and incursion into
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
