<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animal Husbandry Contributes To Agricultural Growth In Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Province has reported
good harvests this year, with animal husbandry helping it thrive
in spite of adverse weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
The summer grain harvest was a record 22.4 billion kg., but
farmers immediately felt threatened by possibly falling prices.
The provincial government intervened, encouraging the development
of animal husbandry and greater grain consumption, and a large
amount of surplus grain was turned into meat, eggs and milk,
pushing grain prices up as a result.
</P>
<P>
In late summer and early autumn, Shandong had one of the worst
droughts in 80 years, but, again animal husbandry played a part in
holding losses to a minimum, and putting 100 yuan more in every
farmer's pocket, by developing some technology-intensive and
market-friendly livestock products.
</P>
<P>
The province's success in curbing fluctuations in agriculture
is attributed at least in part to developing animal husbandry, and
Shandong has grown into the country's largest livestock products
supplier. Animal husbandry uses half the province's grain output,
80 percent of its corn, 20 percent of its wheat, and 30 percent of
its peanuts.
</P>
<P>
This year, the province is expected to produce 6.85 million
tons of meat, 3.89 million tons of eggs, and 760,000 tons of milk,
an all-time high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
