<HEADLINE> Fishery Business Growing In East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 11 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province
expects to produce 1.3 million tons of aquatic products this year,
a 17.4 percent rise from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries have had the fastest growth of all rural sectors,
growing at an average of 33 percent from 1994 to 1996, as a result
of local development projects.
</P>
<P>
Output of the local fishery business is expected to be worth 7
billion yuan this year, up 1.1 billion over the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
The province has 93,000 ha. of fish ponds, 135,000 ha. of fish
farms enclosed by screens, and 40,000 ha. of fish farms in paddy
fields, and there is a growing number of villages with more than a
million yuan in output value.
</P>
<P>
The province has set up more than 2,000 share-holding
fisheries, and has introduced more than 2.5 million US dollars of
overseas investment to set up 23 Sino-foreign joint fishery
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
