<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Charter Change Bid Over, Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Filipino people, the
opposition and investors heaved a sigh of collective relief early
this week when President Fidel Ramos declared his endorsed
candidate for the 1998 presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
Ramos announced Monday that he had chosen Speaker of the House
of Representatives Jose de Venecia as the presidential candidate
for the ruling Lakas-NUCD (National Union of Christian Democrats)
Party in next year's general polls.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine stock market reacted positively to the
announcement, which, among other factors, helped the local
bourse's main index maintain a strong uptrend for the first three
days this week.
</P>
<P>
"It's not because of the selection of de Venecia. It should
have a positive effect (on the market) because a choice was
finally made. It takes away some clouds of political uncertainty
aggravating the currency crisis," a trader said.
</P>
<P>
The much-awaited announcement ended lingering speculation among
the president's critics and investors that Ramos might press on
his bid to ensure his continued stay in power by reviving the
charter change bid or through other hidden plots.
</P>
<P>
In almost the entire year of 1997, however, the country's
years-long political stability and robust economic growth have
been at stake due to a fierce row over whether to change the
Constitution to remove the term limit of Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1987 Constitution, Ramos can only serve a single term
of six years, and must step down in June 1998. The term limit was
designed to prevent a reprise of former dictator Ferdinand Marcos
who ruled the country for 20 years with a high hand.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos' supporters, most of them members of the ruling party
and government officials, claimed that a six-year term was "too
short" for Ramos, who had done a lot in revitalizing the ailing
economy and restoring stability in the country since taking office
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Starting late last year, they launched an unremitting campaign
in the Supreme Court and the Congress in a bid to revise the
charter to allow Ramos run for a second term or extend his present
term.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the charter-change drive was strongly objected by
the Opposition, the influential Catholic Church and even the
business community which had regarded Ramos a "savior" of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who had been ambivalent on the charter-change drive, was
blasted for failing to stop his associates from pushing the drive
and to clarify his political plans in the 1998 polls.
</P>
<P>
Due to mounting pressure from the anti-charter change camp, the
charter-change efforts were blocked both in the Supreme Court and
the Congress in early September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Charter Change Bid Over, Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But Ramos' refusal to categorically announce his objection to
the extension of his term prompted Manila Archbishop Jaime Sin and
former president Corazon Aquino to call a mammoth protest rally in
Manila on September 21, the 25th anniversary of the proclamation
of martial law by Marcos.
</P>
<P>
On that day, more than half a million people from all walks of
life braved heavy rains and trooped to downtown Manila to say "No"
to the extension of Ramos' term.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the grand anti-charter change rally, Ramos backed
off and declared his promise not to run for a second term, calling
for changing the charter after the 1998 polls. He likewise pledged
to hold the 1998 general elections and ruled out the proclamation
of a martial law.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' assurances ended the months-long political unrest in the
country and avoided a political crisis. But speculation still
persisted over Ramo's future political options until this week
when Ramos announced his successor.
</P>
<P>
"The party is now really over for Ramos," said a political
observer who asked not to be named. "The only option left for
Ramos is to catapult de Venecia to the highest post, and then
maybe he can continue to exert influence by working as his senior
adviser. "
</P>
<P>
"As long as there was no (successor) chosen, there will be
doubts on whether or not the presidential elections would push
through," he said, adding that investors' worries over the
country's political instability have been eased somewhat now.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that uncertainty will remain in the political
scene until a smooth transfer of power after the May 1998
presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
Among the proclaimed presidential contenders, Ramos' choice, De
Venecia, is not a favorite for the public. Widely viewed as a
traditional politician, the Lower House speaker has fared poorly
in many independent opinion polls so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Two opposition candidates, Vice President Joseph Estrada and
Senator Macapagal Arroyo, have been leading in almost all opinion
polls. But both have no strong links with the military, whose
support is deemed vital for political stability in a country
having experienced many aborted coups in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, a former action movie star, is popular among the
ordinary Filipinos, but is reportedly detested by the military. A
shadowy military group warned earlier of the election of Estrada
as president, saying they would take drastic actions against this
scenario.
</P>
<P>
Using the powerful government machinery to boost the popularity
of de Venecia will be a pressing task for Ramos during the
remaining months of his term.
</P>
<P>
The Filipino people, who had already made a crucial decision in
the charter change row, will have to make another difficult choice
in the coming elections. The Philippines stands again at a
crossroads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
