<HEADLINE> Common Agenda Urged Among SAARC Nations in WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Sri Lankan Trade
Minister K. T. Wikramaratna today urged member nations of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) to forge
a common approach in tackling trade issues before the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in 1985, embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"Why should the seven different countries of SAARC speak in
seven different voices? The friction between India and Pakistan is
not making things any easier," he told the Press Trust of India
(PTI) here.
</P>
<P>
Given the atmosphere of distrust among some SAARC members, Sri
Lanka would opt to be a spokesman for the region as a neutral
member and voice its concerns, needs and requirements at
international meetings, he said.
</P>
<P>
"While the whole world is grouped into trade blocs, we are
squabbling among ourselves allowing others to exploit us," he
claimed.
</P>
<P>
"Only if we have a common agenda before the WTO can, the South
Asian nations derive benefits for the region from such
international negotiations," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
