<HEADLINE> French Farmers Protest EU Agriculture Policy Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- French farmers will stage a
series of protests on Thursday against the plan of the European
Union (EU) to reform the Common Agricultural Policy (PAC), on the
eve of the EU summit to be held on December 12-13 in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The National Center of Young Agriculture Workers (CNJA) said
that the reform of PAC would mark "the deviation from a new
course of competitiveness and to the enlargement of exploitations."
</P>
<P>
In its "Agenda 2000" reform project, the European Commission,
the EU's executive body, plans to cut the guaranteed prices for
cereals by 20 percent, meat by 30 percent and milk by 10 percent,
while partially compensating the loss of European farmers with a
rise in aid package.
</P>
<P>
The members of CNJA have sent thousands of post cards to
President Jacques Chirac, asking him to "change the things" at the
EU summit.
</P>
<P>
They also demanded that the new PAC "affirms the European model
of agriculture with a human face, which allies men, markets and
territory," instead of letting the market force farmers make
"standardized, trivialized and dehumanized products." 
</P>
