<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Documents on Nanjing Massacre Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese history professor has
released more documents describing Japanese atrocities in China,
on the eve of the 60th anniversary of the Nanjing Massacre.
</P>
<P>
They provide more historical evidence than some previous
documents that stunned the world with their proof of the week-long
barbarity of Japanese soldiers in 1937.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Kaiyuan, a historian at the Central China Normal
University, stumbled on the documents in the theology school at
Yale University during a visit to the United States in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Zhang has studied the Bates Documents, left by Miner Bates, who
was working on a doctoral degree in history at Yale, and who was
in Nanjing for the 30 years before 1950. He helped start the
History Department at Nanjing University, and along with 20 other
foreigners, organized an international aid commission during the
Massacre.
</P>
<P>
He witnessed many of the events of that time and kept the
valuable historical documents. After his death in 1978, his family
donated all the papers to Yale University.
</P>
<P>
In his study of them, Zhang found that Bates and nine American
missionaries had recorded details of the massacre in various
letters, bulletins and research reports,
</P>
<P>
In one comment, written between February and March, 1938, Bates
said that Japanese soldiers had killed at least 300,000 civilians
in their march from Shanghai to Nanjing. The Japanese intruding
troops seized the city of Nanjing on December 13, 1937.
</P>
<P>
Zhang will go to Tokyo and Osaka on December 13 to attend a
special international conference in commemoration of the 60th
anniversary of the massacre. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
