<HEADLINE> FM Office to Guard Interests of Macao: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A top Chinese Foreign Ministry
(FM) official said here today that the FM Macao office that will
begin operation in December 1999 will help maintain China's
national sovereignty and interests and protect Macao residents'
legitimate rights.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yingfan, vice-minister of foreign affairs, told an
audience of about 400 people at the cornerstone-laying ceremony of
the FM office in Macao that the office will be an important
symbol of China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over
Macao.
</P>
<P>
"The office will, in accordance with the Basic Law of Macao,
deal only with foreign affairs of the Macao Special Administrative
Region within the scope of the Central People's Government," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"It will maintain China's national sovereignty and interests,
protect the lawful rights of Macao residents and play its due role
in the long-term stability and development of Macao," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister reiterated that the policy of "one country,
two systems" will be implemented in Macao, adding that both China
and Portugal are making vigorous efforts for a smooth handover of
power and transition.
</P>
<P>
Locating just a few blocks away from the Hong Kong-Macao port
terminal, the building sits on a land area of more than 6,000
square meters. It will have a total construction space of 19,000
square meters and is about 45 meters high with eight floors,
housing both offices and residences.
</P>
<P>
The construction will be completed in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qiren, director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch,
who is on an official trip to Beijing, sent a message of
congratulations, pledging Xinhua's full support to and help for
the construction.
</P>
<P>
Present at the ceremony were Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira
and Chen Ziying, deputy director of the Hong Kong and Macao
Affairs Office under the State Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
