<HEADLINE> World Bank Release 42M$ Credit to Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Finance Minister
Ronald Panza said today that the World Bank has decided to grant
Zambia 42 million U.S. Dollars credit to support its balance of
payments, according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
ZANA quoted Panza as saying here during a news release that
the decision was made by the bank during a meeting held Tuesday
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
This is the second tranche of the credit to be released to the
country. The first part was made available to Zambia in 1996 to
support the government's economic recovery program.
</P>
<P>
Panza said the bank's decision indicates that it considers the
country to be fully on course with the implementation of the
recovery program and recognised the government's good performance
and management of economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
He added that the bank is aware that good results have been
obtained under the program such as the dropping of inflation from
30 percent in 1996 to 15.7 percent during the first 11 months of
1997 and the restoration of the growth momentum of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's economic recovery program, which is designed by the
World Bank and the International Monetary Foundation (IMF), aims
at not only increasing economic growth but also at higher rates
of proverty reduction, a more efficent public sector, sustained
human resource investments and more effective safety net
provisions.
</P>
<P>
At present, two missions from the World Bank and IMF are
holding talks in Lusaka with the Zambian government on the
financing of the country's economic reform program for 1998.
</P>
