<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: "One Country, Two Systems" Successful in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Everything has proved that
Hong Kong continues to be as usual after its return to China on
July 1, said Douglas Henk, Chairman of the American Chamber of
Commerce (AmCham).
</P>
<P>
Five months after the handover, the Hong Kong people are
leading their lives in ways they are used to and the big changes
some people predicted before the handover did not take place after
July 1, Henk said in an exclusive interview with Xinhua at his
office.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, Henk has been an active member of the AmCham, which
is a non-partisan, non-profit business organization with a mission
to foster the development of commerce between the United States,
Hong Kong and the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He was elected chairman of the largest American chamber of
commerce outside the United States in 1996 for a one-year term
beginning January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Henk said many people predicted that the Hong Kong government
would operate under instructions from Beijing after July 1, but
the situation now has been exactly the opposite.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) is running Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
Henk, who has been working in Hong Kong for 11 years, said that
the Chinese characters for "crisis" mean both "danger" and
"opportunity" and he thought that the recent financial crisis in
Asia has offered China a good opportunity to tell the world how
the SAR government deals with its affairs in its own way.
</P>
<P>
The Central Government has shown its respect for and support to
the measures taken by the SAR government to defend the pegged
exchange rate between the Hong Kong dollar and the U.S. dollar,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Henk, who has been to China's inland areas many times,
said: "The good news is that China itself is weathering this
economic crisis pretty well. For a couple of times China had to
go to the controlling mechanism to make sure that the economy did
not get overheated," Henk said. This should be good for Hong
Kong, he added.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, Henk led a delegation to Washington to
persuade U.S. President Bill Clinton to extend the Most Favored
Nation (MFN) trading status to China unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
He told Clinton that granting permanent MFN would stabilize
U.S.-China relations but revocation of MFN would damage Hong Kong,
undermining confidence during a critical transition period.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1969, AmCham has established channels of
communication and ongoing dialogue between the chamber and
governmental bodies in Hong Kong, the United States and China's
mainland.
</P>
<P>
AmCham often organizes seminars and conferences for business
executives at various levels. AmCham's Publications Department
has published a number of trade and commerce resource books on
doing business in the area.
</P>
<P>
Looking to the future, Henk is confident about Hong Kong's
prospects although he predicted that Hong Kong's stock market would
continue to be volatile for a period.
</P>
<P>
He believes that the SAR government will succeed in upholding
the pegged exchange rate. "The policy of the HKSAR to defend the
peg is quite right and the peg has been very good for Hong Kong,"
Henk said.
</P>
<P>
There are some pains now, but it will be good in the near
future, he noted. "If we were to drop the peg right now, the
short-term benefit will be relatively small and we will lose
whatever benefits we've gained pretty quickly."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is a place where people come for reasons that go
beyond Hong Kong, Henk said. There are a large number of
multinational companies which choose to put their regional
headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
There are five favorable factors of doing business in Hong Kong
-- geographic location, communications network, infrastructure,
free port and taxation, and most of the 1,200 member companies of
the AmCham plan to expand their business here, Henk said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
