<HEADLINE> Northwest China Oilfield Producing More Oil, Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Changqing
Oilfield, in the Erdos Basin, on the juncture of Gansu, Shaanxi
and Shanxi provinces, and the Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia
autonomous regions, is expected to produce 3.3 million tons of
crude oil this year, 1.9 million tons more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
The oilfield has 300 billion cu.m. of proven gas reserves,
making it the country's biggest, and oil reserves are expected to
reach 640 million tons, according to the Changqing Oil Exploration
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Its first oil well was sunk in 1907. In the past eight years,
the administration has increased exploration in Mesozoic to
Palaeozoic Era layers, and in gas exploration.
</P>
<P>
In this way, it has found 244 billion cu.m. of gas and can
produce 840 million cu.m. of natural gas a year and has built
China's biggest gas purification plant.
</P>
<P>
Recently completed pipelines began sending gas to Xi'an, the
capital of Shaanxi, in July, and to Beijing in August.
</P>
<P>
The administration has said it will work harder to bring its
oil output to five million tons by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
