<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues Regulations to Protect Yungang Grottoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A set of regulations on the
protection of Datong Yungang Grottoes has been put into effect in
north China's Shanxi Province with approval from the National
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The regulations involve financial resources for the protection
and maintenance of the grottoes, construction controls in the area
and other legal guarantees, said Wang Heng, head of the Cultural
Relics Research Institute of the Yungang Grottoes.
</P>
<P>
Yungang Grottoes is one of China's three major groups of
artistic grottoes, along with Dunhuang in northwest China's Gansu
Province and Longmen in central China's Henan Province, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 45 grottoes were built in the middle of the Fifth
Century. They contain 51,000 statues, mainly of Buddhist
figures. The tallest statue stands 17 meters high; and the
smallest, two centimeters.
</P>
<P>
Located in one of the country's major coal production centers,
the Yungang Grottoes has suffered serious pollution damage from
dust, cinders and acid rain stemming from the mining industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, structures such as factories and
residential houses which have nothing to do with the grottoes
should be removed from the protected area. The regulations also
ban demolition for mines and stone quarries.
</P>
<P>
Vehicles carrying coal and garbage must be covered when passing
the road in front of the grottoes, according to the regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
