<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Japan Launches Six Major Reforms in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto ambitiously vowed in January to work for
wide-ranging reforms in the national bureaucracy, fiscal and
economic structures, the financial, social welfare and educational
systems, which attracted worldwide attention.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said if all reforms in the six areas turned out to be
successful, Japan would experience a third rejuvenation following
the Meiji Restoration and the post-war reconstruction of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The reforms were initiated because the problems in these areas
had fettered the social progress.
</P>
<P>
The current world economy has been undergoing a rapid
development toward globalization and an era is approaching when
manpower, products, capital and information flow freely and
businesses enjoy choices to favor countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The high costs of the Japanese economic structures, however,
have increasingly squeezed its industrial, employment and
financial sectors so that they are hollowing out.
</P>
<P>
To illustrate, the total trading volume of the Tokyo stock
market ranked first in the world in 1989, whereas it was less than
30 percent of that in the New York stock market in 1995. Owing to
a great number of restrictions on the Tokyo financial market, and
high tax rates and brokerage commission fees, the number of
foreign companies listed in the Tokyo securities market dropped
from over 140 in 1989 to about 70 in 1996. Many foreign banks and
securities firms have withdrawn their headquarters from Tokyo for
the same reason.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, low birth rates, the aging population and the
shrinking work force have depleted the vigor and vitality of the
Japanese economy and society, worsened financial operations and
created hidden perils to the economic growth and social security
system in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
To achieve a sustainable growth, the Hashimoto administration
viewed it imperative to perform a major operation on various
systems established in the post-war period of more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
This year, the Japanese government finally set the reforms in
motion and scored some initial achievements, which are as follows:
</P>
<P>
First, an administrative reform plan has been finalized which
aims at forming a "leaner government" and strengthening the
centralization of the government. The current 22 government
ministries and agencies are to be reduced to 13 by the year
2001. A related bill will be submitted to the Diet (parliament)
early next year and special bodies to streamline the bureaucracy
are expected to be set up next summer.
</P>
<P>
Second, Japan's House of Councillors passed a fiscal reform
bill which stipulates that the aggregate amount of central and
local government deficits should be reduced to less than three
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) by the 2003 fiscal
year and called on the government to stop issuing deficit-covering
national bonds.
</P>
<P>
Third, the reform on the financial system has produced a new
system of mutual penetration by banks, securities and insurances,
which allows banks to establish holding companies and relaxes the
restrictions of various commission fees. Starting from 1998, the
revised foreign exchange law will go into effect and all banks
will enjoy free convertibility of currencies.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, the "action plan" for the reform of economic structure
worked out by the cabinet in May will be revised by the end of the
year. Accordingly, electricity and gas prices will be duly lowered
and the restrictions on economic activities relaxed.
</P>
<P>
Fifth, as for the social welfare system, a reform bill on
medical insurance has been framed and will be submitted to the
next Diet. The bill mainly covers abolishing the medicine pricing
standards by 2000 and revising the medical awarding system. The
pension deliberative council has decided to start working on the
pension reform program early next year, to lower the amount of
pension and set an older age for people to receive pension.
</P>
<P>
Finally, an amendment act on educational reform, which aims to
implement a consistent junior-to-senior middle school system
starting from 1999, has been drawn up and will be submitted to the
next Diet for passage.
</P>
<P>
Despite the achievements, the long-delayed reform programs have
met strong resistance as they are not thorough and involve various
aspects of the Japanese society and the vested interests of many
people. This also helps explain why no leaders prior to Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto had enough courage to put the package
of reform programs on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The release of the interim and final report on administrative
reform caused a public outcry. Some people thought Hashimoto's
move was nothing but a superficial operation. In view of the past
reform attempts, some people cast doubts on the government's
resolve and feared it would turn out to be "a change in form but
not in essence".
</P>
<P>
The Nihon Keizai Shimbun said that despite the achievements,
the administrative reform program will not go any farther but
result in the "overlapping" of the central government
organizations for its failure to specify how to decentralize the
power of the central government and how many staff members will be
cut. The newspaper pointed out that in so doing, it would also
create a hotbed for those who abuse power for personal gains.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties brought forth sharp criticisms. The leader
of the New Frontier Party Ichiro Ozawa said the administrative
reform and its program "fell short of their names and lacked
philosophy and essence." The Sun Party, however, viewed it as
nothing but "a sheer random change and stopgap". The Sankei
Shimbun said the government's administrative reform move was a
fine start and a poor finish.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, despite the formation of the reform act on the
fiscal structure, remarkable questions still persist such as the
separation of the Finance Ministry's fiscal and financial
functions and the reform on the pension system.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the current continuous bankruptcies in the
financial world have also intensified people's worries about the
possible premature end of the economic resurgence. The Japanese
media held that the key factor in the economic restructuring lies
in the government's daring and resolve to relax various
restrictions on the economy. The reform on the medical care system
and the reduction of the pension remain to be hard nuts to crack
in the reform of the social security system.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have noted an eye-catching point in the six reforms
advocated and pursued by the Hashimoto administration is that they
conceal a strategic intention to turn Japan into a political power
which will play a more important role in the international
political arena. The proposal raised by some Diet members of the
Liberal Democratic Party in the administrative reform debates to
upgrade the Japanese Defense Agency to Defense Ministry is an
ominous signal to people who wish the reforms will be able to be
carried forward in the direction of peaceful development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negative Growth In China's Retail Price For November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The retail price index in
China for November had a year-on-year growth of -0.8 percent, or
0.5 percent lower than October's, according to the State Planning
Commission today.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index was up 1.1 percent from the same
period last year, but down 0.3 percent compared to October's
figure.
</P>
<P>
From January to November, the two indexes rose 0.9 percent and
3 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Food prices in general were down, manufactured goods remained
stable by and large, and service-related items posted big
increases.
</P>
<P>
According to a commission report, 12 of the 31 provinces,
autonomous regions, and municipalities directly under the central
government reporting showed growth at or below the national
average, with prices in Shanghai, Jiangsu and Anhui 1.1 percent,
0.6 percent and 0.5 percent lower than the national average,
respectively. The other 19 reported growth greater than the
national average, with Beijing, Qinghai, and Sichuan 3.9 percent,
3.1 percent, and 3.1 percent higher than the national average,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Of China's 36 major cities, 19, including Nanjing, Xiamen and
Shanghai, were at or below the national average, while Beijing,
Xining, Chengdu and 14 others were above the national average.
</P>
<P>
New Year's Day and Spring Festival are approaching and
departments are being urged to ensure adequate supplies of goods
and stable prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
