<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Travellers Cheque Project Stranded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The west African travellers
cheque project has been stranded with the pullout of the
Francophone countries at the last minute, casting shadow over the
sub-regional effort to introduce a single currency by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Promoted by the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), ECOWAS travellers cheque is scheduled to be launched
this month as a prelude to the attainment of the goal of single
monetary zone.
</P>
<P>
However, at the meeting of the Committee of ECOWAS Central
Bank governors in Dakar, Senegal, the Francophone members (BCEAO)
withdrew their participation from the project over the failure of
all debtor banks to settle their arrears of debts.
</P>
<P>
According to Tony Ede, Nigeria's central bank spokesman who
was at last week's Dakar meeting, BCEAO attributed the pullout to
the refusal of some countries to settle their trade arrears
contracted through the west Africa monetary agency, the
sub-regional clearing mechanism.
</P>
<P>
BCEAO specifically asked that until full settlement of payment
arrears are made, it would not be possible to introduce the
cheques, Ede said, quoted by local press today.
</P>
<P>
BCEAO represents the interest of such Francophone countries as
Benin, Burkina Faso, Cote D'ivoire, Guinea Bissau, Mali, Niger,
Senegal and Togo.
</P>
<P>
Sources, however, attributed the sudden withdrawal of BCEAO
from the scheme to fear among the Francophone countries on the
possibility of a single currency in the sub-region that could
produce a negative effect on their CFA currency.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Times pointed out that France, which still wields
immense influence in these countries, might have dissuaded them
from participating in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
The idea of ECOWAS travellers cheque was mooted in 1987 as a
means of coordinating trade transactions with the sub-region.
Regional central bank governors finally agreed last August that
the checque would be launched this month.
</P>
<P>
The cheque, which would have been in circulation by January 28
next year, is also expected to usher in an era of common currency
to further boost economic activities within the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
According to the Nigerian central bank spokesman, all
necessary arrangements have been made for the launching of the
cheque, including the printing of the cheque and other publicity
materials.
</P>
<P>
If BCEAO stands firm in its resolve, the money expended so far on
the project would be lost, Ede said.
</P>
<P>
But effort was said to be in top gear to woo back the BCEAO
group to the scheme in order to ensure the take off of the cheque
soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Financial Crisis Increasingly Deepens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Trading at the Seoul foreign
exchange market stopped just three minutes after the South Korean
won rocketed to 1,719.8 against the U.S. dollar today from the
previous day's 1,565.9.
</P>
<P>
The composite index at the country's stock market plunged 14.95
to 384.9 points as of 10:07 a.m. even though the 50 percent
increase in foreign investment limit, which was promised by the
South Korean government during negotiations with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) for a bailout program, became effective today.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts here said the won would soon soar to 2,000
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
After the trading stopped at the foreign exchange market, South
Korean Deputy Prime Minister Lim Chang-yuel convened officials for
an emergency meeting at the Ministry for Finance and Economy to
discuss a measure of persuading IMF to deliver all of its promised
21 billion dollars in loan within this year in a bid to calm the
trembling financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based IMF planned to loan nine billion
U.S. dollars to South Korea before 1998.
</P>
<P>
The financially troubled country, which had ordered 14 merchant
banks' suspension of business operation in the past 10 days to
ease jitters in the financial market, said that it would need
about 20 billion dollars to boost foreign currency flows.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the South Korean people on TV this morning,
South Korean President Kim Young-sam said his nation would face
greater financial troubles if it failed to regain the trust of the
international community.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his nation should undergo a fundamental
restructuring in economy for a revitalization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
