<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO: Most Women Still Kept Away From Top Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Most women continue to suffer
from occupational segregation in the workplace despite rapidly
increasing rates of female education and participation in the
workforce worldwide, according to a report released here today by
the International Labor Organization (ILO).
</P>
<P>
While women have made substantial progress in closing the
gender gap in managerial and professional jobs, most female
managers worldwide are still barred from the top levels of
organizations, whether in the private or public sector or in
political life, the ILO said in its new report entitled Breaking
Through the Glass Ceiling: Women in Management.
</P>
<P>
"Glass ceiling" is a term coined in the 1970s in the United
States to describe the invisible artificial barriers, created by
attitudinal and organizational prejudices, which bar women from
top executive jobs.
</P>
<P>
"Almost universally, women have failed to reach leading
positions in major corporations and private sector organizations,
irrespective of their abilities," in spite of the overall progress
of women in middle management, said ILO labor expert Ms Linda
Wirth, author of the report.
</P>
<P>
The ILO will hold a tripartite meeting involving
representatives of governments, employers and workers from 20
countries worldwide on December 15-19 in Geneva to discuss the
findings of the report and examine the situation of working women
in management.
</P>
<P>
The participants will seek to develop action strategies
designed to provide more and better jobs for women, especially in
management and top-level positions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
