<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Remains Depressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
remained depressed today, with stronger-than-expected employment
data overshadowed by ongoing concerns over depressed gold prices
and the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished the session at 66.70 US cents,
down from 66.75 US cents locally late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank corporate foreign exchange senior dealer
Stavros Nitis said the Australian dollar rallied 25 points after
the release of the data, to a high of 67.15 US cents, but failed
to sustain its gains.
</P>
<P>
Total employment rose 70,900 to 8.52 million, adjusted, in
November from 8.45 million in October, the Australian Bureau of
Statistics said.
</P>
<P>
The market had expected a rise of 15,000 in employment.
</P>
<P>
Australia's unemployment rate was a seasonally adjusted 8.4
percent in November, the same as in October.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think the market's attention is really on unemployment
data, I think it's still gold, Asia, South Korea, Japan," Nitis
said.
</P>
<P>
"The best you can probably expect is a bit of a short squeeze,
or a knee jerk reaction higher in offshore trading tonight, but I
wouldn't expect the Aussie to go any higher than 67.40 US cents or
thereabouts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jeremy Colless from ANZ Investment Bank said that "the
interpretation is that, at the moment, employment may be picking
up but with the Asian crisis descending to new depths today people
feel that the Australian economy next year may suffer."
</P>
<P>
Against the Japanese yen this evening, the Australian dollar
was at 86.19 yen from 86.69 yen Wednesday. It was also at 1.1904
German marks from 1.1957 marks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
