<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Drop in Asian Domino Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
lost ground today as a pre-emptive drop ahead of an anticipated
softening on Wall Street tonight in reaction to a further fall in
key Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 37.9 points, nearly 1.5 percent
to 2,516.8, with the problems spread over resource and industrial
stocks, large and small.
</P>
<P>
It came off a low of 2,506.2 points as the Hong Kong and
Japanese markets continued to fall.
</P>
<P>
"It's definitely attributable to that (Asian and US fall),"
Henderson Charlton Jones dealer Scott Emms said.
</P>
<P>
"There are concerns in the States that this Japanese banking
and financial crisis is going to have impacts there," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Wall Street overnight stocks fell, led by technology and
banking shares, as Asia's economic crisis continued to erode
profits of US multinationals.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 63.7 points down at 4,310.5,
with News Corp one of the main sufferers as its recent
improvements came to a halt.
</P>
<P>
ANZ Bank shares were sold down as investors shied at its large
Asian exposure. ANZ shares fell 30 cents amid general falls in
banking stocks.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank fell 23 cents, Commonwealth dropped 25
cents and Westpac fell 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
Resource stocks were again sold down on the Asian concerns,
with the all resources index down 17.4 points to 1,086.7.
</P>
<P>
WMC shares fell 19 cents while BHP shares dropped 18 cents to
its lowest level this month at 13.77 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks generally rose as the bullion price improved by
0.60 to 284.60 US dollars per ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for the day was 343.57 million shares at a
value of 900.64 million Australian dollars (603.42 million US
dollars), with falls outnumbering rises 681 to 354.  
</P>
</TEXT>
