<HEADLINE> Israel's Current Account Deficit Shrinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Israel's current account
deficit shrank in the first nine months of this year to 3.786
billion U.S. dollars, a 29.7 percent drop compared with the same
period in 1996, The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted an announcement published by Israeli Central Bureau
of Statistics Wednesday as saying that it was a dramatic drop as
the current account deficit of the first three quarters in 1996
amounted to 5.387 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for the reduction was the relatively stable
level of imports, while exports increased. For example, combined
imports of goods and services will total 32.827 billion dollars
this year in comparison with 32.444 billion dollars in 1996,
while exports will increase from last year's 22.419 billion
dollars to this year's 24.157 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In July, the Treasury predicted the current account balance of
payments will show a 3.6 billion dollars deficit in 1997, with a
reduction to 3.1 billion dollars next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
