<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Plunge on Pessimism Over Public Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stock prices plunged
Thursday in reaction to a remark by the Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto that public funds will be used only for the
ailing financial system, but not for revitalizing the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange decreased by 427.97 points or 2.60
percent from Wednesday's closing of 16,050.15.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, fell 25.42 points or 2.05 percent to
1,215.74.
</P>
<P>
Most market participants took a wait-and-see stance, monitoring
talks on the proposal to float 10 trillion yen (7.7 billion
U.S. dollars) worth government bonds to restore confidence in the
deteriorating financial system.
</P>
<P>
But when they heard the reports that Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto wants to infuse public funds generated through bond
issuance only to stabilize the financial system, but not to prop
up the economy, disappointment spread in the market.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 410 million
shares, up from Wednesday's 396.25 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Hokkaido Takushoku Bank was today's most actively traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,329 issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 939 to 187, with 132 issues unchanged. 
</P>
