<HEADLINE> Ancient Rice Paddy Unearthed In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists in central
China's Hunan Province have found the remains of paddy fields
beneath some ancient city walls 6,000 years ago, in Lixian County.
</P>
<P>
The paddy fields, stems, husks, roots, and leaves of rice
plants, and ponds and ditches used for irrigation all provide
evidence of rice cultivation dating back 6,000 years.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of rice seeds dating back 8,500 years have
also been found at nearby Chengtou Mountain, where cultural
relics were first unearthed in 1991. The ruins are the earliest of
ancient cities so far in China.
</P>
<P>
The relics include city gates, dwellings, porcelain production
areas, roads and tombs. The place was put on the list of cultural
relics under state protection in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
