<HEADLINE> China Sees Informal ASEAN Summit as Important Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- An official said here today
that China regards the upcoming informal summit meeting among 12
East and Southeast Asian countries as an important event which
will contribute to cooperation among these countries.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Foreign Minister Chen Jian made the remark at a press
briefing today prior to Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
participation in the informal summit among the nine ASEAN
countries and China, Japan and the Republic of Korea (nine plus
three) and a similar summit between China and ASEAN this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Chen disclosed five items on the agenda of the nine-plus-three
meeting, namely the prospects for the 21st century for East Asia;
global relationship; the particular relationship between Asia and
Europe; cooperation in order to maintain economic stability in the
region; deepening regional economic contacts and cooperation; and
coordination and cooperation on international economic issues.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang will have a wide-ranging discussion with his
counterparts at the nine-plus-three meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We will also highlight the important role East Asia will and
has continued to play in the world as a whole," he added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, President Jiang will meet with leaders of all the
heads of state or government at the meetings, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
China became a full dialogue partner of ASEAN in July of
1996. Bilateral consultation between China and ASEAN has been
conducted mostly at the foreign minister-level until now.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first high-level contact between ASEAN and
China. The issues on the agenda for discussion between Jiang and
leaders of the member nations will involve relations between ASEAN
and China toward the 21st century, including guiding principles,
political issues, economic issues, cooperation between China and
ASEAN as well as other issues of common concern, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will issue a joint statement which is expected to
target a relationship of military trust and good-neighborliness
and the framework for an ASEAN-China relationship for the 21st
century, Chen added.
</P>
<P>
It will also embody a number of principles to guide this
relationship, as well as a number of detailed contents so that
this relationship will be characterized by all-round cooperation
and good-neighborliness, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the South China Sea, Chen said it is left over
from history, and good bilateral channels exist between China and
relevant countries for a peaceful settlement of any disputes.
</P>
<P>
China hopes, within the framework of shelving disputes and
entering the joint development, to gradually settle this issue,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
Through consultations between China and ASEAN in recent years,
both sides are convinced that the maintenance of peace and
stability in the region serves as a precondition for economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have realized that the development of friendly
relations, cooperation, good-neighborliness and mutual trust serve
the overall interests of both sides, he said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides maintain that disputes over the issue of the South
China Sea should not affect the development of friendly relations,
nor should it affect peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, disputes between concerned countries should be
solved through bilateral talks and discussions from the
perspective of maintaining peace and stability, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that China supports the treaty on a nuclear-free zone
in Southeast Asia. However he said this nuclear-free zone includes
a continental shelf and an exclusive economic zone and that is why
China and other countries are now consulting with ASEAN members to
find a way that China can join the protocol of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to work to this end," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
