<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Knesset Passes Law Against PNA Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset
(parliament) has passed a legislation preventing the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) from conducting census in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The legislation passed its third and final reading Wednesday
night by a vote of 26-11. The new legislation is an amendment to
the law on the implementation of the Oslo Accords, which was
aimed at preventing the PNA from taking a census in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The original legislation prevents the PNA "from opening or
operating offices or holding meetings within the state of
Israel," while the new version broadens this ban to include
"activities."
</P>
<P>
The government's speedy move to submit a Knesset bill to block
a PNA census in Jerusalem followed a suggestion by
Attorney-General Elyakin Rubinstein, who said there are loopholes
in the law, which is known officially as the Gaza/Jericho
Agreement Implementation Law (limiting of activities) passed by
the Knesset in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
It restricts PNA activities to Gaza and Jericho and bars any
PNA activity "of political or government nature...which does not
coincide with respect for Israel's sovereignty" in Israel
without the Israeli government permission.
</P>
<P>
But the law did not cover eventualities. While it could
prevent the holding of PNA meetings in Israeli areas, it could
not restrict the PNA from holding a census.
</P>
<P>
A ministerial committee headed by Justice Minister Tzahi
Hanegbi convened urgently Tuesday night to prepare an amendment
that could enable the Israeli police to prevent a PNA census in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The ministers approved the draft amendment by phone Wednesday
morning, since there was no time to convene the cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The issue of how the public perceives its stand on the unity
of Jerusalem split the Labor Knesset faction.
</P>
<P>
After heated discussions, the Labor members of parliament
decided Wednesday by a vote of 16-8 to support the government
bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian FM: Outcomes, Not Headlines, on Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government is
seeking outcomes instead of headlines through dialogues on human
rights with China, visiting Australian Minister for Foreign
Affairs Alexander Downer said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I do not believe that the diplomacy that has been conducted
through the United Nations Commission on Human Rights toward China
has been successful," Downer told a press conference at the
Australian Embassy today.
</P>
<P>
"The old route was not productive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Australia was one of the first countries that quit
co-sponsoring resolutions against China before the U.N. Commission
on Human Rights, he said: "What the Australian government is about
are outcomes. We are not about headlines for the sake of
headlines. We are not about headline-hunting."
</P>
<P>
He said that Australia had a human rights dialogue with China
in August and will talk again in June. He said that Australia will
back-up the dialogues with an increasing number of
development-assistance projects in the broad area of developing
human rights in China, including a publicity network for promoting
women's rights.
</P>
<P>
"Initiatives like these are effective, practical and
cooperative, rather than just a bit of confrontation once a year
in the United Nations forum," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I mean that, OK, you have the confrontation. You have the
vote. Then what do you have?"
</P>
<P>
He said that because all seven attempts to pass a resolution
against China by the U.N. commission have failed, "China has been
able to demonstrate that it is able to use its influence on the
United Nations Commission on Human Rights and to overthrow, year
after year, a resolution.
</P>
<P>
"We are taking a more productive and more considered path to
the future.
</P>
<P>
"It requires a good degree of cooperation with China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"From our perspective, this relationship in the area of human
rights is progressing at this stage in a constructive way," Downer
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed appreciation that many other countries, except the
United States, have followed Australia's lead on the human rights
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
