<HEADLINE> PNA Seeks Closer Economic Links with Israel: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) would like to form a regional economic bloc with
Israel, according to a report of today's The Jerusalem Post.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Said Bamia, director-general of the PNA
Ministry of Economic Affairs and Trade, as saying that "the
Palestinians seek political separation and economic integration,
integration in the style of the European Union or EFTA (European
Free Trade Association)."
</P>
<P>
"We in the PNA have found that the development of economic
ties between the two private sectors is already significant,
especially for the development of the Palestinian economy,"
Bamia added.
</P>
<P>
But he criticized the Israeli customs authority's requirement
that "Israel" be marked on import documents as a destination
point, even in cases when the products are headed exclusively
for the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Israeli customs authority also requires Palestinian
importers to sign a guarantee that such products won't be sold
in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The PNA, meanwhile, outlined a three-year development plan
for 1998-2000, which will be submitted today to the donor states.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for investments of 3.5 billion U.S. dollars,
of which 600 million dollars are designated for projects in
progress. Donor states also have been asked to approve a second
five-year assistance plan for the territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
