<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Leader Meets U.S. Pacific Commander  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Chi Haotian, vice-chairman of
China's Central Military Commission, met here today with Joseph
Prueher, commander-in-chief of the U.S. Pacific Command.
</P>
<P>
Extending a warm welcome to Prueher on behalf of the Chinese
Ministry of National Defense, Chi, also a state councillor and
minister of national defense, said Sino-U.S. relations have made
great strides over the past year, and that President Jiang Zemin's
visit to the United States has, in particular, turned out to be
very successful.
</P>
<P>
Describing Jiang's visit as a major event of great historical
importance in bilateral relations, Chi said that President Jiang
and US President Bill Clinton decided at the summit to make
concerted efforts to set up a 21st-century-oriented constructive
strategic partnership by way of increasing cooperation and
promoting world peace and development.
</P>
<P>
The summit served to provide historical opportunities for
further increasing Sino-U.S. relations in the future, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to join hands with the US to remove all obstacles
to achieving the goal of increasing understanding, expanding
common grounds, developing cooperation and ushering in the
future," Chi said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Taiwan issue is still the most sensitive
problem in the bilateral relationship and that he hoped the United
States would observe the three joint communiques and statements
signed between the two nations, and in earnest follow its promises
on this issue.
</P>
<P>
Chi went on to say that the contacts between the two armies
have been rather active through joint efforts this year, and
bilateral relations are developing smoothly. He also said he hoped
this momentum would be maintained next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
