<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Hails China's Grant of Destination Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government and
tourism industry today welcomed China's decision to approve
Australia as one of several officially designated tourist
destinations for Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard today welcomed the
approval, saying, "That will unlock the capacity for tens of
thousands of Chinese citizens to visit Australia without having to
get and make special passport arrangements."
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer earlier announced
that Australia has won approval from the Chinese government as a
designated tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
Downer said this would provide a substantial boost to the
Australian tourism industry and is an important development in
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Tourism Minister Andrew Thomson said the
minister looked forward to using his Mandarin language skills to
cultivate these bilateral tourism ties during his visit to China
in February.
</P>
<P>
"More than 54,000 Chinese visited here last year. But now they
can use ordinary passports and apply for tourism visas, there is
huge potential for growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Tourist Commission (ATC) said the move would
create thousands of new jobs in Australia and make travel to
Australia easier for Chinese holidaymakers.
</P>
<P>
"Previously, travel to Australia by Chinese nationals had been
largely restricted to business-related visits," ATC Managing
Director John Morse noted in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"This one decision will create thousands of jobs all around
Australia and bring into Australia a significant increase in
foreign exchange earnings."
</P>
<P>
The ATC would now accelerate plans to open an office in
Shanghai by early next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Tourism Task Force said the decision by the most populous
nation in the world to first expose their citizens to Western
culture using Australia would provide a welcome boost to a
flagging industry.
</P>
<P>
Australia has thus joined only five other destinations holding
approved destination status - Macao, the Philippines, Thailand,
Malaysia and Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
