<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Arafat to Meet in London: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat are set
to meet in London next Thursday, the English daily The Jerusalem
Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu-Arafat summit will take place next Thursday
within 24 hours of their planned separate meetings with United
States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in Paris and Geneva,
an Israeli Foreign Ministry official was quoted by the paper as
saying.
</P>
<P>
But the official conceded that there is possibility of a
last-minute change in venue or date for the Netanyahu-Arafat
summit, which if convened will boost the momentum for advancing
the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Radio reported today that the Israeli
government is prepared to hand over about 13 percent of the West
Bank to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) in the second
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The report said this was according to a map drawn jointly by
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon after secret consultations.
</P>
<P>
Among the 13 percent handover, 10 percent come from Area C
under sole Israeli control and the rest from areas near Jenin,
Nablus and Hebron within the Area B, which is under Israeli and
Palestinian joint control.
</P>
<P>
Both Mordechai and Sharon are members of the four-man
ministerial committee charged with formulating the scope of second
redeployment in the West Bank and Israeli position on the
permanent talks with the PNA. The committee headed by Netanyahu
includes Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
The committee has already held three sessions to draw a map
on the further redeployment and final-status talks, but has
failed so far to produce an agreement due to reported inner rift
on Israel's security interests in the final settlement.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that while hardliners Netanyahu and
Sharon favored creating expansive security zones along the Green
Line and Jordan Valley, moderates Levy and Mordechai insisted
that such zones could be much smaller.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial panel is to reconvene this afternoon in
another effort to make progress before Netanyahu's scheduled
meeting with Albright next week.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who held two meetings with Netanyahu in Paris last
week, has been pressing Netanyahu to come out with a concrete and
more credible decision on the second redeployment. The United
States is reportedly demanding for at least 12 percent for the
second redeployment, rather than the 6-8 percent originally
proposed by Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
