<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Cotton Production Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has harvested a raw
cotton of 70,000 tons in 1997, a record high since 1975 when the
country won its independence.
</P>
<P>
Erasmo Muhate, director for the Mozambican Cotton Institute,
was quoted by today's Noticias as saying that the harvest is much
higher than the 53,000 ton goal set for the year.
</P>
<P>
The country turned out 51,000 tons of raw cotton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Muhate attributed the harvest to the prevailing peace and the
rising cotton price on the world market.
</P>
<P>
About 200,000 families are engaged in cotton planting on an
area of 130,000 hectares, and 11 companies are also planting
cotton on 147,000 hectares of land, with 10,000 employees
involved.
</P>
<P>
Cotton is Mozambique's third export commodities. It is
estimated that the country would export cotton valuing 33 million
U.S. Dollars this year, over the 28.5 million U.S. Dollars export
last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
