<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 08:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Egypt Sends Message of Defiance to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 11 (Xinhua) -- When veteran Oscar Best Actor
Omar Sherif stood on the stage in front of the Hatshepsut Temple
in Luxor, southern Egypt Wednesday night, he was not just there
to perform. He has a message to convey.
</P>
<P>
"From beautiful Thebes which has infused the world with its
radiance; From the temples that gave man his sanctity of
soul,... the (Egyptian) people wish to express to the world their
deepest apologies and condolences," Sherif read out the message
at a ceremony at the scene of a cold-blooded massacre to
thousands of intense-faced audience who came to pay their tribute
to the victims of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
With candles and roses as well as music and arab songs, Egypt
mourned the 58 foreign tourists and four Egyptians, who were killed
on November 17 in front of the Hatsheput Temple, an ancient
necropolis, in the Valley of Kings in Luxor, about 500 kilometers
south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
"Thebes Message to the World," conveying Egypt's anguish at
the massacre and determination to track down terrorism, was
written by Naguib Mahfouz, the 86-year-old Nobel Prize laureate
and prominent novelist who himself survived a terrorist attack in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The ancient city of Thebes, now known as Luxor, fell captive
by terrorism. As a result of the carnage, the city which includes
some of the world's greatest monuments, has been abandoned by
foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
As Sherif's deep voice flying in the whistling gust lapping
the Valley of Kings, a group of Nubian drummers donned in white
robes lined up on the platform of the temple, the very spot where
the killings took place, beating out a mournful tune amid the
swirling bonfire smoke and thick wind dust.
</P>
<P>
After Verdi's "Tears of Anger" was played by Egypt's best
symphony and orchestra troupes, the audience lit candles to
commemorate the victims and placed flowers at the scene of the
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
These were part of the funeral ceremony organized by the
Ministry of Culture and attended by 4,000 guests including
President Hosni Mubarak, a number of ministers and Islamic
leaders as well as senior diplomats of 30 countries.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuko Okazaki, the 26-year-old Japanese graphic designer,
nodded in agreement as she heard the message. She and her friend
Hiroshi Otani tripped on the requiem when touring the Valley of
Kings Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Okazaki told Xinhua that she heard of the Luxor tragic when
touring in Spain and then decided to continue her booked 10-day
trip to Egypt, a country "too great to be missed."
</P>
<P>
Looking around the car-loads of armed policemen and
numerous security checkpoints, the two Japanese young tourists
said they felt very safe.
</P>
<P>
However, they said, due to the lack of Japanese tourists,
EgyptAir, the Egyptian airline, has cancelled all its direct
flights between Tokyo and Egyptian cities, forcing the handfuls
of hardy tourists to transit in other countries.
</P>
<P>
Ten Japanese tourists, including a couple on their honeymoon,
were killed on November 17, when six Islamic militants slashed
and gunned down 58 foreign tourists and four Egyptians in front
of the temple on the west bank of Luxor.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, as Luxor's big hotels reporting rarity of foreign
tourist groups and shop-owners sitting idle by the side of empty
streets, Luxor, the city that thrived on tourism, has turned into
a deserted city.
</P>
<P>
Ali, the owner of a gift shop taking a vantage place in front
of the temple, complained that the massacre has virtually killed
his business. "The last time I sold a three-pound stone necklace
was two days ago when an Egyptian preparatory school group came
here," he said.
</P>
<P>
As foreign tourists rushed to cancel their bookings, the
government has taken a string of measures including encouraging
domestic travelling to prevent a tourism crash. Tourism has been
Egypt's back-bone industry that brought in 3.6 billion
U.S. dollars and nearly 3.9 million tourists in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The "message" delivered at the requiem is just a beginning of
a series of cultural and popular events that Egypt will host in a
campaign to boost its image as a safe tourist haven, according to
Minister of Culture Farouk Hosni. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Indonesia to Jointly Manage Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Indonesia
today agreed to make joint disaster management and relief efforts
in the wake of July's haze crisis resulting from forest fires in
Indonesia and affecting several neighboring countries including
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding (MOU), signed by Malaysian
Information Minister Mohamed Rahmat and Indonesian Minister for
People's Welfare Utama Azwar Anas, spells out cooperation in joint
operations including deployment of personnel, equipment, search
and rescue missions, training and information exchange.
</P>
<P>
Under the MOU, covering a three-year period, Kuala Lumpur and
Jakarta will host alternate bi-annual meetings to discuss
disaster-related collaboration.
</P>
<P>
The MOU is automatically renewable for another three years
after the original three-year time span unless either country
chooses to terminate it by giving a six-month notice.
</P>
<P>
The MOU is crucial as next year Malaysia would be hosting two
key events, namely the Commonwealth Games and the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum conference, Mohamed said at a joint
press conference with Azwar after the signing.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully with the MOU, both sides can react promptly and
activate rapid response to future forest fires," Mohamed said.
</P>
<P>
Last July's haze in Malaysia forced the government to declare
an emergency in Sarawak, which lasted for 10 days, incurring
substantial economic losses.
</P>
<P>
In this context, the MOU requires both countries to control the
disaster at source at their own expenses and according to their
own laws and procedures.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, which also suffered extensively from the forest
fires in Kalimantan and Sumatera, has tightened its environmental
protection laws by banning open burning.
</P>
<P>
Azwar said the recent fires destroyed 165,361 hectares of
forest in Indonesia, causing damage estimated at 134 billion
rupiah (about 4 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He added that Indonesia has learned a lot from the forest fires
and the resulting haze and has drawn up preventive measures to
avoid a recurrence.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are under way to train national and local-level
authorities in forest fire management similar to those undertaken
to deal with volcanic eruptions, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
