<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monk Studies Chinese Literature in Yunnan University (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A young Buddhist monk, wearing
his gown and beads, gets in touch with common lives in a
university, but not theological one.
</P>
<P>
Monk Renkong from Panlong Temple, 60 kilometers from
Kunming-based Yunnan University, spends more time reading literary
works than chanting Buddhist scriptures.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first monk that Yunnan University has enrolled in
its 70-year history," said Xu Yangfu, director of the university's
Student Administration Office. Xu added that religious personnel
have always been allowed to receive a higher education.
</P>
<P>
Renkong, 24, already had studied for three years in Fujian
Buddhist Theological Institute, several thousand kilometers away
from his hometown.
</P>
<P>
"Freedom of religious belief in China includes equal education
opportunity among all people," said Na Zhonglun, director of the
Yunnan Provincial Religious Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Monks and nuns also can study in secular education
organizations in addition to theological ones, Na said. However,
most religious people still choose theological institutes, which
can provide special treatment and plan particular courses for
them, he said.
</P>
<P>
With his love of ancient Chinese literature, especially poems
in the ancient Tang and Song dynasties, Renkong persisted in
starting his university life as a literature major. After
obtaining support from his temple, he came to Yunnan University, a
renowned study center in southwest China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East African Standard Buys Kenya's KTN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The East African Standard
company has bought the privately-owned commercial station of
Kenya Television Network (KTN) for an undisclosed amount, the
East African Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper said that the acquisition of KTN marks the
start of a new era in the development of the Kenyan media.
</P>
<P>
The takeover announced here Wednesday brings together the
country's oldest newspaper and Kenya's only major privately-owned
television station, it added.
</P>
<P>
Bob Holt, Managing Director of the East African Standard, was
quoted as saying Wednesday that the combination would make the
group a leader in the media industry in the East African country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the combination would lead to a more
comprehensive news services for TV views while advertisers would
receive the combined sales expertise and unique marketing
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The media official pointed out that "the future rests with
integrated media groups in order to maximize efficient use of
resources and offer the widest marketing solutions to clients."
</P>
<P>
Holt announced that plans were already underway to expand the
station beyond the confines of Nairobi and the immediate
surrounding area.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "we have, for some time, been exploring the
possibility of launching or acquiring both television and radio
stations as part of the newspaper group's strategic development."
</P>
<P>
KTN which was launched in 1990 will become part of what the
Standard management describe as Kenya's first integrated media
group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
