<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Calls Human Right Activists to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Uganda President Yoweri
Museveni advised human right activists to go to rural areas to
help local people to eradicate poverty, The Monitor reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In a written speech read yesterday by Emmanuel Kirenga, the
State Minister for Justice and Constitutional Affairs, the
president told the newly created Human Right Peace Center
(Huripec) that there is greater need for human rights' education
and empowerment in Ugandan rural areas than at an university.
</P>
<P>
"The center must not confine itself only to dissemination of
human rights principles on the campus, it must reach down to the
grassroots", the president said.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating Huripec at Makerere University here, the state
minister said Uganda now is on the road of constitutional
democracy and no single individual can divert the process.
</P>
<P>
A strong civil society keeps government on its toes and
enables the development of a health dialogue between the
government and its people, he added.
</P>
<P>
Huripec is co-funded by Makerere University, the United States
Agency for International Development program and the faculty of
law of Makerere University.
</P>
<P>
Huripec is the second of its kind in Africa after South
Africa's. 
</P>
