<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Shipping Industry to Adopt ISM Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- China plans to adopt the
International Safety Management (ISM) Code among local companies
engaged in international shipping, in a bid to improve management
quality and viability in the world market.
</P>
<P>
By July 1, 1998, 103 of the country's 250 international
shipping companies' vessels should meet the code's requirements.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Baochen, an official in charge of shipping safety from
the Ministry of Communications, made the announcement at today's
closing session of the Second Conference of the China Shipowners'
Association.
</P>
<P>
The ISM code is designed for the safety of management and
prevention of pollution among local vessels involved in
international shipping, Zhang said, and to improve the managerial
level of international shipping companies and the safety of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the code would force the country's shipping
industry to give up its traditional managerial model and prevent
management errors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang stressed that implementation of the code should be
regarded as a crucial reform in the shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China has 250 firms involved in
international shipping, with more than 1,300 vessels with a total
capacity of 23 million tons, ranking fourth in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
