<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Shipowners' Association Conference Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The three-day Second China
Shipowners' Association (CSA) Conference closed here today.
Vice-Minister of Communications and CSA Honorary Chairman Liu
Songjin and Chairman Chen Zhongbiao were re-elected.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, representatives from 177 CSA members held
heated discussions on the country's shipping market, the
difficulties local firms are facing, industry reforms and the role
of CSA.
</P>
<P>
The participants shared the view that Chinese shipowners have
to survive in a growingly competitive market by depending on their
own efforts. They also expressed the hope that the government would
take measures to create an equal and fair market environment for
shipping companies.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jiafu, managing director of the Tianjin branch of the China
Ocean Shipping Company and president of the Tianjin Shipowners'
Association, said that the only way out for local shipping firms
is to adopt scientific managerial methods and modern enterprise
systems.
</P>
<P>
He asked local shipowners to avoid vicious domestic competition
and to be united against overseas competitors.
</P>
<P>
Participants agreed that CSA should play a bigger role as the
bridge between shipowners and the government, serve as the
industry's information center and coordinate local and foreign
shipping companies.
</P>
<P>
The association was founded in Beijing in 1993, with the
country's major international shipping firms as its members.
</P>
<P>
CSA Secretary General Liu Xuezhong told Xinhua that China has
more than 250 international shipping companies with more than
1,300 vessels operating on international routes and a capacity of
23 million tons, fourth in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
