<HEADLINE> U.S. Senator's Allegation on Chinese Bonds Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for China's
central bank today denied an allegation by a U.S. senator that
Chinese bonds issued in the United States are very likely to be
deceptive, saying that China enjoys credibility in issuing bonds
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The allegation of the U.S. senator is utterly groundless and
here I express my regret over these irresponsible remarks," the
spokesman for the People's Bank of China said here.
</P>
<P>
Chinese government departments and institutions have to date
issued 4.72 billion U.S. dollars in bonds in the United States,
with two-thirds of the amount bonds of sovereignty or
quasi-sovereignty ratings issued by the Ministry of Finance and
the State Development Bank, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the commercial issuers are all-powerful Chinese
banks or non-banking financial institutions with good credit.
</P>
<P>
Information in relation to the bonds has been fully disclosed
in accordance with relevant U.S. regulations on the administration
of bonds, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that all the bonds were registered with the Securities
and Exchange Commission and given ratings higher than the
investment grade by Moody's and Standard &AMP; Poor financial rating
systems.
</P>
<P>
The funds raised through the bond issues have been invested in
civilian projects in infrastructure, high-technology and exports,
the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
