<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 Springs Discovered in East China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 springs have been
discovered in Jinan, known as the "city of springs" in east
China's Shandong Province. There are nearly 500 known springs in
the city.
</P>
<P>
The city lies to the north of Mount Tai and to the south of the
Yellow River and has a unique topography. By the Jin Dynasty
(1115-1234) the city reportedly had 72 springs which attracted
numerous travelers and scholars. The springs are still a source of
tourism income.
</P>
<P>
Last June, the city had 293 springs in addition to the original
72.
</P>
<P>
After that, the city's Springs Protection Office inspected
those sites and discovered another 200, which have quietly gushed
for hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
Most of the newly discovered springs are on the outskirts of
the city, with some found in residential courtyards.
</P>
<P>
The city's Springs Protection Office has invited experts to
inspect the sites and name them. After approval by the city
government, each spring will be put under special protection and
opened to the public.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
