<HEADLINE> UNDP-Backed Northeast Asian Development Program Continues (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A multi-billion-US-dollar
development project along the Chinese, Russian, and Korean borders
has been moving ahead with its road, railway and
telecommunications work in an underdeveloped area.
</P>
<P>
Joining China, Russia and the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea in the project are the Republic of Korea, Japan, and
Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
But, Prof. Ding Shicheng, an advisor to the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) who is known as the "Father of the
Tumen River Project", says, "It was very difficult for the program
to go so quickly in just six years under such complicated
international circumstances."
</P>
<P>
The UNDP began the project in 1991 as a priority item in East
Asian development, and it plans to raise 30 billion US dollars
within 20 years to build the area into an international
communication, transport, trade, and financial center like Hong
Kong or Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government also places great emphasis on it, and
puts it on the list of three trans-century national projects,
along with the Three Gorges Project and Shanghai's Pudong New
Area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
