<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP-Backed Northeast Asia Development Program Continues (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four billion yuan has been spent by China's central and local
governments on power plants, coal mines, railways, urban
infrastructure, and airports.
</P>
<P>
The city of Huichun, which is located at the heart of the
triangular area, used to be at the bottom of the barrel.
</P>
<P>
But since 1992, when the central government declared it an open
city, a highway network has been taking shape, and the city's
three border crossings have a combined cargo handling capacity of
900,000 tons, and in the first half of the year, had nearly
250,000 people and over 370,000 tons of goods.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese are busy building a highway linking Huichun with
Changchun, the capital of Jilin Province, and Fangchuan, a small
town near Russia and the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Russia has completed work on a railway to China that will
become operational next year and has expanded a border crossing
with a 240 million-US-dollar bank loans from Japan.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK has spent 50 million US dollars annually on the Rajin
Pioneer Free Economic and Trade Zone and 120 million US dollars of
foreign capital has been used for the construction of hotels and
telecommunications facilities there.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK plans to introduce 7 billion US dollars worth of
foreign investment to electrify a railway link with Quanhe, a
Chinese border city. In 1995, local companies opened regular
service to Rajin and Chongjin and to Vladivostok in Russia,
cutting the distance, freight costs and amount of time needed to
move goods from Japan and ROK.
</P>
<P>
A new 40,000-line programmable telephone network also allows
local people to make direct calls to 180 countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
