<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Repairing Cultural Ruins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Automonous Region is raising funds for large-scale
renovations at more than 10 ancient relics sites.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,000 ruins in the region have been damaged by
erosion and people, especially architectural ruins dating back
1,300 years which urgently need to be repaired, said Yue Feng,
director of the region's Bureau of Cultural Relics Administration.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has already poured 10 million yuan (about 1.2 million
U.S. dollars) into the repair project of Kezi'er Thousand-Buddha
Cave in Baicheng since 1983, saving one-third of its grottoes.
</P>
<P>
Restoration work at the Site of Jiaohe City in Turpan started
in 1993 with a Japanese investment of one million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the bureau expedited research and excavation at
the Loulan and Niya ruins.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists from China and Japan have found silk fabric and
other precious relics at Niya.
</P>
