<HEADLINE> China, Japan Join Hands to Develop New Minivan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Japanese
automakers have jointly introduced a new minivan model, the first
ever such Sino-Japanese joint development.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing Chang'an Automotive Co., one of China's leading
mini-vehicle producers, cooperated with Japan-based Suzuki in
developing the model, called the SC6350, which was designed to
meet the needs of Chinese consumers and equipped with
state-of-the-art devices.
</P>
<P>
The two partners made the first prototype SC6350 in
1996. Manufacturing is set to start in July of 1998, with products
later exported to Japan.
</P>
<P>
China introduced foreign auto models in the mid-1980s. The
country's auto authorities in recent years called for the local
manufacturers to develop copyrighted models in a bid to enhance
the competitive edge of local producers. 
</P>
