<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Chef Sets Noodle Stretching Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese chef in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region made more than 65,500
noodles as thin as hair by stretching a dough weighing one
kilogram (2.2 pounds), according to a report in the Shanghai-based
"Xinmin Evening News", which was seen here earlier.
</P>
<P>
The total length of 65,536 noodles was 99,600 meters after they
were connected one by one, breaking a Guiness World Record, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Li Enhai, the record-setter who is working at the Five-Star
Mansion Hotel of Urumqi, capital of Xinjiang, spent only 20
minutes on stretching the noodles.
</P>
<P>
The 49-year old chef used nothing but water and salt to knead
the dough. "But proper temperature and moisture content in the
dough are very important," the chef said.
</P>
<P>
Li has practiced the noodle-stretching skill for more than 20
years, including eight years in China's best kitchens in Diaoyutai
State Guesthouse and the Great Hall of the People in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Hand-stretched noodles have been a favorite on Chinese dining
tables for centuries, even though the large variety of
machine-made noodles provide residents with greater convenience
today.
</P>
<P>
Noodles are an important part of various celebrations like
birthday parties, because many people still believe that long
noodles symbolize longevity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
