<HEADLINE> Philippine House Speaker on Vice Presidential Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine House of
Representatives Speaker Jose de Venecia, the ruling party's
candidate for the 1998 presidential elections, has ruled out the
possibility of choosing a non-party member as the vice president
bet.
</P>
<P>
"That is technically possible but it is impossible," he said,
explaining that the ruling Lakas-NUCD party has three aspirants to
the vice-presidency and they all meet the staunch qualities of a
good partner, the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The three aspirants are Interior and Local governments
Secretary Robert Barbers, Senator Leticia Shahani and Justice
Secretary Teofisto Guingona.
</P>
<P>
The speaker made the statement in response to reports that
Senator Gloria Macapagal Arroyo, leader of a small opposition
party, wants to join him in the elections.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia added that since he is from Luzon, the northern part
of the country, the vice presidential candidate must be from the
central or the southern part to create a balance in governance.
</P>
<P>
This also rules out President Fidel Ramos' sister, Senator
Leticia Shahani, from the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party is expected to announce its candidate for vice
president during the weekend or early next week.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos chose de Venecia Monday night as the ruling
party's standard bearer in next year's elections.  
</P>
