<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Eliminate Child Labor by 2010 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh plans to end all
forms of child labor by the year 2010, according to State Minister
for Labor and Manpower M. A. Mannan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the three-day 12th Asian regional meeting of the
International Labor Organization (ILO) being held in Bangkok,
Thailand, Mannan said his country has almost eliminated child
labor in ready-made garment industries and it plans to abolish it
in hazardous industries by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh respects workers' fundamental rights and has so far
satisfied six core ILO conventions, reflecting the country's
commitment to the principles of freedom of association and
collective bargaining, prohibition of forced labor and
non-discrimination, the state minister was quoted by the national
news agency BSS today as saying.
</P>
<P>
Though the other conventions are yet to be ratified, there has
been substantial implementation and reflection "in our laws and
practices," he added.
</P>
<P>
The International Program on Elimination of Child Labor has
been under effective implementation with donor assistance since
1995, Mannan said, adding that the program will remove the last
vestiges of child labor in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Despite substantial improvement in the employment situation,
Bangladesh has 11 million unemployed at present, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The government has given priority to the expansion of
vocational and technical education for skill development in a bid
to overcome the problem, the state minister said. "Such programs
will continue in the future."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
