<HEADLINE> Economic Growth Potential Improves in Central, Eastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Central and Eastern European
countries will see faster economic growth next year, the Czech
News Agency (CTK) quoted the British magazine, The Economist, as
saying here today.
</P>
<P>
A report carried in The Economist said Poland will be one of
the fastest growing economies in that part of the world next year,
with a 5.3 percent rate of increase.
</P>
<P>
The Czech economy will also start to improve. The growth rate
will reach 3.3 percent. Romanian and Bulgarian economies will
increase by 4.4 and 3.5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The countries along the Baltic Sea will see an increase of 4 to
5 percent. The Russian economy will increase by 2 percent, and the
Ukraine by 1 percent. The Slovakia Republic will slow down to 3.3
percent from 6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland will be among those
doing the best in average domestic national production (DNP) in
the central European countries next year, with 4,680, 4,470 and
3,570 U.S. dollars per person.
</P>
<P>
The report also pointed out, though the economic growth in the
area is increasing, there are still a lot of problems remaining
such as a huge budget deficit, a high inflation rate and a high
unemployment rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
