<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lung Operation Performed on Fetus in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The first-yet operation on a
six-month-old fetus was conducted in Costa Rica one month ago,
Dr. Gerardo Escalante, head of the maternal-fetal medicine unit of
the Calderon Guardia Hospital, disclosed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Escalante said that so far, both mother and the daughter, who
will be born on February 12, are in good health.
</P>
<P>
The fetus had a congenital malformation in her right lung,
which was detected during the fourth month of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
A six-centimeter-long cyst was in the fetus' lung, which had
begun to exert pressure on the heart and the lung itself.
</P>
<P>
Doctors told the 35-year-old mother that only an operation
could save the baby from death prenatally or at birth.
</P>
<P>
The objective was to remove the liquid produced by the cyst
inside the lung by suction and install a valve to drain the liquid.
</P>
<P>
A catheter was inserted into the mother's abdomen to reach the
fetus, and the process of puncturing the fetus's back and lung was
especially delicate, said the doctors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
