<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee-Growing Areas in Colombia Shrink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's coffee-growing areas
decreased by 14 percent from 1980 to 1997, a survey issued by the
national coffee information system said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that the total coffee-growing area was
1,009,579 hectares in 1980 but dropped to 869,157 hectares by the
end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The reduction was partly due to diversification programs, which
have had a significant impact on the use of land for income
purposes and the protection of biological diversity in
coffee-growing areas.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey revealed that in Colombia's 16 coffee
growing states, the number of coffee growers had increased since
1970.
</P>
<P>
The number of families engaged in coffee growing grew to
566,230 in 1997, from 392,945 in 1970.
</P>
<P>
The increase was due to coffee-growing areas being divided into
smaller and smaller fields which descendants of traditional
coffee growers had. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
