<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Akmola Becomes Permanent Capital of Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- President Nursultan
Nazarbayev of Kazakhstan announced Wednesday that the city of
Akmola will become the nation's "permanent capital" from December
10, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev made the announcement at a government-parliament
joint meeting held at the presidential palace in Akmola, according
to the Kazakhstan Telegraph Agency (KazTGA).
</P>
<P>
From now on, Nazarbayev said, Akmola will be the heart of the
country where important policies towards the 21st century would be
produced and activities of economy, science and technology,
communications and telecommunication carried out.
</P>
<P>
He noted having a "permanent capital" in Akmola, part of the
openning up policy of Kazakhstan, is because of Akmola's important
geographical position bordering on Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of governments and international organizations
including U.N. secretary general Kofi Annan and Chinese President
Jiang Zemin have congratulated Nazarbayev on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Also at the meeting, Nazarbayev made 1998 a National Unity And
History Year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
