<HEADLINE> Palolathi, Martinsen Take Sprint Titles at Nordic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Ari Palolathi of Finland and
Bente Martinsen of Norway won their first ever World Cup
victories in sprint events at the Nordic Cup in Milan, Italy, on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Palolathi, stole the victory from Thobias
Fredriksson of Sweden in the two-way men's final over a
one-kilometer distance on a ring of artificial snow at a cycling
track.
</P>
<P>
World Cup defending champion Bjorn Daehlie was unexpectedly
knocked out in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Daehlie, a world and Olympic champion and the top seed, still
stood atop the World Cup standings after two individual races,
with 132 points.
</P>
<P>
Palolathi moved to second place overall with 100 points, ahead
of Thomas Alsgaard of Norway, who finished fourth in Wednesday's
sprint.
</P>
<P>
In the women's sprint final, debutant Martinsen captured the
title at an all Norwegians contest.
</P>
<P>
Russian Elena Vaelbe, who lost the quarter-final run to
France's Sophie Villeneuve, slipped to 12th place in the women's
standings led by Martinsen with 180 points.
</P>
<P>
The World Cup continues at Val Di Fiemme, northern Italy, over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The women skiers will compete in the 5-kilometer classic and
20-kilometer relay freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Male skiers will run the 10-kilometer individual classic and
the 15-kilometer freestyle. 
</P>
