<HEADLINE> Three-party Consortium Taps Nuclear Possibilities in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Westinghouse Electric Co of
the United States has organized an international consortium with
Spanish and Japanese partners to tap the Chinese nuclear market,
it was announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted analysts as saying the group is
expected to be a powful competitor when China selects its next
partner for nuclear power projects because it can combine
financing from the three countries.
</P>
<P>
However, no signing for a direct project between Westinghouse
and China will emerge before the US Congress officially lifts
the sanction on the export of nuclear power technology to China,
which is hopeful to take place some time earlier next year.
</P>
<P>
According to Charles Pryor, president and chief executive of
the U.S. company, Westinghouse "is doing a lot of preliminary
design work for nuclear projects in China."
</P>
<P>
The company is co-operating with the China National Nuclear
Corp. (CNNC) to develop a new generation of nuclear power plants
-- called the CAP600 megawatt -- for the next century.
</P>
<P>
Such design will combine the technology of Westinghouse's most
advanced AP600 megawatt design and the AC600 megawatt design
developed by CNNC.
</P>
<P>
Pryor said at a nuclear power localization seminar held by the
State Planning Commission Wednesday in Beijing that his company
has submitted a highly detailed localization plan to the
commission.
</P>
<P>
Westinghouse has already transferred steam-generating
technology to Shanghai Boiler Works for the second phase of
construction of the Qinshan Nuclear Power Plant in Zhejiang
Province, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
