<HEADLINE> Modified Cotton Seed to be Used in North China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-U.S. joint venture
producing genetically modified cotton seed started operation
yesterday in Shijiazhuang, capital of north China's Hebei
Province, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The company, named Hebei Jidai Cotton Seed Technology Co, has
4.2 million U.S. dollars of capital and was jointly formed by
US-based Monsanto Corp., Delta and Pine Land Co. and Hebei
Provincial Seed Co..
</P>
<P>
The seed breeding company will sell the genetically modified
cotton seed, called "Boll-guard", to local farmers, who are
expected to plant the seeds in 200,000 ha. of field in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Hebei Province now has about 4,733 ha. of cotton grown out of
the genetically modified seed introduced from the United States,
which proved a 20 percent yield increase from the ordinary
local seeds in the past three years of pilot planting, said Ji
Junqun, director of the Hebei Provincial Seed Administration
Station.
</P>
<P>
With the use of new seeds, an average rural household can save
about 4,500 yuan (about 540 U.S. dollars) per ha. of cotton
compared with the expense of using locally developed seed.
</P>
<P>
Monsanto will launch two or three joint ventures in an effort
to explore the possibility to localize modified seed of such
plants as wheat and corn, according to Paul Johanson. head of the
Agricultural Sector of Monsanto China Operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0268 </DOCNO>
