<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Protect Ancient Papermaking Skill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Hotian City of northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region is trying to retain an
ancient papermaking skill by making it known to more and more
people.
</P>
<P>
Reyaz Ihan, a 62-year old Uygur woman who is the owner of the
city's only mulberry papermaking workshop and is believed to be
the only successor of mulberry paper making, receives lots of
visitors to her workshop every summer.
</P>
<P>
Apart from increasing her income, the move is designed to
encourage more local people to pick up the mulberry paper making
skill popular in the area for more than 500 years, a city official
said.
</P>
<P>
Mulberry paper is made of bark of mulberry trees and the
mulberry paper had been the main writing material in the Hotian
before the founding of new China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Reyaz Ihan said her papermaking tool is handed down from her
grandfather-in-law and she expected to hand it down to the coming
generations.
</P>
<P>
She said, in the past, the mulberry paper was well sold but
things all changed with the spreading of the modern white paper.
</P>
<P>
The old woman explained that her paper would only be used  to
wrap up traditional Chinese medicine or lining of hats of Uygur
people.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the move, a villager has already started to learn
the papermaking skill from the old woman and she often goes to the
villager's home to offer her instructions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Further Regulate Cultural Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- China is to draft a series of
laws and regulations to better manage its theaters, arts galleries
and other institutions, the Ministry of Culture announced.
</P>
<P>
The documents include regulations on the management of the
entertainment industry, on business in the fine arts sector as
well as on the supervision of the cultural market, says Meng
Xiaosi, vice-minister of culture.
</P>
<P>
The cultural sector is flourishing, she said. However, there
exist certain "unhealthy tendency and out-of-order operation," she
added. The fundamental way to solve the chaos in the cultural
market is to use law, she noted.
</P>
<P>
China's introduction of a market economy has enabled the people
to have more choices and voices in the cultural sector, but there
are also new problems such as rampant copyright piracy,
money-worship philosophy, and the selling of pornographic and
violent materials.
</P>
<P>
Meng said that local governments and departments have worked
out many regulations to deal with the situation since
1993. Currently, the cultural market is regulated mainly by
regulations drafted by the State Council. The future goal is to
map out a general law on the management of the cultural market,
according to Meng.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the State Council promulgated a regulation on
the management of commercial performances, the first example that
the state uses the weapon of law to regulate the sector.
</P>
<P>
Meng urged cultural officials and workers to better manage the
market by investigating big cases, and form management networks at
both the central and local levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
