<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Opposition Party Not to Contest Local Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's main opposition
party, the United National Party (UNP), has decided not to contest
the local government elections in the north.
</P>
<P>
The party's working committee took the decision after
considering the situation in the north, where the rebel forces
are active despite a strong presence of government troops, local
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The party also quits the polls on the ground that there are no
proper polling registers for the electorate.
</P>
<P>
Nominations for general elections to municipal, urban and
village councils in Jaffna and Kilinochchi districts in the north
are to be received from December 16 to 23.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka held its local elections in all but Northern province
and parts of Eastern province last March. The elections had been
scheduled for 1995 but were postponed twice for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Besides the UNP, many Tamil parties, including the country's
biggest Tamil party, the Tamil United Liberation Front (TULF),
have expressed their reservations on the coming polls. Some of the
parties even asked the government to postpone the polls to a later
date.  
</P>
</TEXT>
