<HEADLINE> Zambia Denies Cancelling Friendlies With Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian High Commission in
Nigeria denied Wednesday that its government has cancelled two
friendly matches with the Super Eagles, Nigeria's national soccer
team.
</P>
<P>
The high commission said in a statement here that the matches
will go on as scheduled and that media reports to the effect that
the matches had been put off were false.
</P>
<P>
"The government of the Republic of Zambia has already
authorized the issuance of visas by the high commission in Lagos
and the South African High Commission too, has authorized their
transit visas," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Bizwayo Nkunika, the Acting Zambian High Commissioner was
quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria as saying that arrangements
have been concluded for the smooth transit of the Super Eagles
through Johannesburg to Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
"The Zambian High Commission in Pretoria has been directed to
meet the 31-man contigent and facilitate their smooth transit," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The trip to Lusaka of the Nigerian players is to be financed by
the Zambian government. They are expected to play against the
Zambian national team on Sunday December 14, in Lusaka, and again
in Kitwe on December 17.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the Zambian government has cancelled
the matches because of the sports sanctions on Nigeria imposed by
the Commonwealth, of which both Nigeria and Zambia are members.
</P>
<P>
Nkunika said the Zambians would use the friendlies to prepare
for the African Cup of the Nations Cup scheduled for February in
Burkina Faso and would also use the opportunity to avenge its
defeat by Nigeria at the Tunisa '94 Cup of Nations final. 
</P>
