<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Associates, Fujitsu Launches Jasmine Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Computer Associates
International, Inc. (CA), the leading business software builder of
the United States, and its Japanese partner Fujitsu Limited
Wednesday jointly launched the first pure object-oriented database
software Jasmine.
</P>
<P>
"For years, object technology has been long on promise and
short on reality, forcing programmers to learn complex languages
and cobble together nonintegrated databases and tools," said CA
Chairman and CEO Charles B. Wang.
</P>
<P>
"That's why we teamed with Fujitsu, developer of world class
object database technology, to jointly develop and globally market
this breakthrough technology," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jasmine differs from all other database management products on
the market today, Wang said. It offers programmers and
non-programmers an object-oriented platform ideally suited for
dynamic multimedia applications in their business management.
</P>
<P>
Since it is so powerful in managing multimedia data, including
bitmaps, animation, audio and full-motion video, the CA people
called it a "revolutionary product."
</P>
<P>
It supports such a wide range of "next-generation applications"
from electronic commerce to industry-specific applications in
sectors such as insurance, financial services, health care and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Jasmine as one of the cornerstones of its vision for
the future, Computer Associates places high hope on the new
product. The company sold 4 billion U.S. dollar worth of software
in 1997. That still makes Computer Associates arguably the third
largest software company after Microsoft and Oracle.
</P>
<P>
CA now pays greater attention to its presense on the Asian
market. It just set up a new technology center in India.
</P>
<P>
On cooperation between CA and its Chinese partners, Wang said,
"one of the things CA and I myself can help is to bring into the
Chinese market what a role of technology is. It's a great
tool. Don't reinvent everything. There is tremendous
technology. How do you add value above and how do you use it."
</P>
<P>
There are a lot of things CA can do with the Chinese, he said.
Apart from bringing Chinese students and business people over to
study in CA, the company is also asking some software developers
in Shanghai to write codes for it, said Wang, who founded CA in
1976 and brought it to the public in 1981.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese market place and talent base are tremendous," he
noted. But the Chinese have less knowledge about the market and
they need to understand how to develop and market their products.
</P>
<P>
"Jointly and cooperatively, we can do a lot," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0281 </DOCNO>
