<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Face Human Rights Violations at Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States, while
always grading human rights records of other countries, is facing
a wide range of human rights violations at home, said a study
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A poll, commissioned by Human Rights U.S.A. to mark the
anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights,
indicated that 63 percent of Americans said that the poor were
usually discriminated against in U.S. society.
</P>
<P>
Half or more of the 1,004 adults surveyed last month also named
the disabled, the elderly, gays and lesbians and native Americans
as routinely discriminated against, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
Forty-one percent of those surveyed said black Americans
routinely suffered discrimination, and 70 percent of blacks
themselves said they felt discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
In grading their country's performance in human rights, three
in four Americans said that if the country's founding fathers
returned today they would be "disappointed with the way things are
going in the country," Peter Hart Research Associates said.
</P>
<P>
Hart told a news conference Wednesday that Americans felt U.S.
social programs fall short in affordable health care,
environmental protection and helping the poor.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, U.S. President Bill Clinton talked about human
rights violations in a number of foreign countries in a speech
marking the anniversary of the 1948 declaration.
</P>
<P>
However, Lyn Beth Neylon, director of Human Rights U.S.A., said
Wednesday, "The survey shows we have human rights problems right
here in the United States." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
