<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Standards For Coding Tibetan Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The "compilation of characters
of the Tibetan language code" has passed two national reviews and
has been designated as an important part of the international
standard, China's leading newspaper "People's Daily" reported this
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new development of the language code has marked a new stage
for the Tibetan language in modern information exchange, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The development of the code which was jointly sponsored by the
State Technical Supervision Bureau, State Nationalities Affairs
Commission and the Ministry of Electronics has laid a foundation
for the processing of the Tibetan language and exchanges through
computer networks.
</P>
<P>
The code standard will be applied next year, which will allow
the Tibetan language to play a larger role in the development of
information technologies and international exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Most of China's ethnic groups have languages of their own and
some of them have their own writing, the major tools for social
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
China has attempted to preserve and improve its ethnic
languages, standardizing them for the modernization of information
processing technologies.
</P>
<P>
Application systems have been developed for processing the
language information of such ethnic groups as Mongolian, Tibetan,
Hui, Korean, Hani, Dai and Yi.
</P>
<P>
The languages of these ethnic groups are applied widely in
publishing, education, publicity and administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fish Exports from Chile Rise 7.9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 10 (xinhua) -- Chile's fish exports
increased 7.9 percent in the first ten months of this year,
compared to the same period of 1996, said the national fishing
association.
</P>
<P>
Export shipments reached 1.606 billion U.S. dollars in the
January to October 1997 period, which points to a new 1.8 billion
dollar record for this year.
</P>
<P>
Frozen exports rose 26 percent, canned products
went up 32 percent, refrigerated fresh products increased 10
percent, and seaweed and derivatives were up 7 percent. 
</P>
