food deficit in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Times:
</P>
<P>
-- President Fidel Ramos Wednesday dismissed as mere
"grumblings" the threat of supporters of former Defense Secretary
Renato de Villa to launch their own movement and push for his
presidential bid in 1998. Ramos anointed Monday night House
Speaker Jose de Venecia as the presidential candidate of the
ruling party instead of de Villa.
</P>
<P>
Today:
</P>
<P>
-- Public suspicion that the 24 kidnappers recently arrested by
the anti-kidnapping team are "fall guys" was bolstered Wednesday
with the disclosure by some police officers that some of them have
long been in police custody and that none of them is on the list
of kidnappers in Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
Business World:
</P>
<P>
-- The Central Bank of the Philippines Wednesday took a further
step to reduce interest rates by lowering its overnight borrowing
rate and relaxing its overnight lending conditions.  
