<HEADLINE> Top IRA Prisoner Reported to Have Escaped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 10 (Xinhua) -- At least one terrorist prisoner
is believed to have escaped from Northern Ireland's top security
Maze jail near Belfast, local press reports said tonight.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed republican prisoner, who was serving a life
sentence, was reported missing after a Christmas party for
inmates' children at the jail.
</P>
<P>
"The Northern Ireland Office has received reports from the
Prison Service that it would appear that a prisoner has gone
missing this evening," said a government spokesman
</P>
<P>
He added that "checks and investigations are proceeding. A
further statement can be expected from the Prison Service later."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a major security operation has been
mounted and the motorway which passes close to the jail has been
sealed off.
</P>
<P>
The prison is reportedly Europe's most closely guarded
guerrilla jail and is used to hold around 300 republicans and
about 270 loyalist paramilitary members.
</P>
<P>
The suspected jail break happened on the eve of historic London
meeting between British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Gerry Adams,
president of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican
Army (IRA). 
</P>
</TEXT>
