<HEADLINE> hke121101#-#- Chinese Leader Li Ruihuan Arrives in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan,
a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of the Chinese
Communist Party (CPC) Central Committee, arrived here at 8
a#.m#.local time (3 a.m. Beijing time) today, to start his
four-day official goodwill visit to New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Li, also chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, is making the
trip at the invitation of the government of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
In a written speech at the airport, Li said that this year is
of great significance in the relations between China and New
Zealand because the year witnessed the 25th anniversary of the
establishment of diplomatic relations between the two countries
and centenary of the birth of Rewi Alley, an envoy of friendship
from New Zealand and a great friend of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad to note that in the 25 years, especially in
recent years, our relations have scored positive achievements in
such fields as politics, economy, science and technology, culture
and education," Li said.
</P>
<P>
China and New Zealand, both located in the Asia-Pacific region,
hold common and similar views on many major international and
regional issues, Li said, adding that there are both sound basis
and broad future for the further development of China-New Zealand
relations, which not only conform to the fundamental interests and
common aspirations of the two countries and peoples but also
contribute to the development and stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese government has all along attached
importance to its relations with New Zealand, and "I come to New
Zealand with the wish to strengthen friendship, enhance mutual
understanding, expand cooperation and promote the all-round
development of the bilateral ties."
</P>
<P>
"I am looking forward to exchanging views with leaders of New
Zealand on our bilateral ties and international and regional
issues of common interest," Li noted. "I hope and believe that,
through the joint efforts of the two sides, this visit will
promote the further development of China-New Zealand friendly
relations and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Li came to New Zealand from the Ho Chi Minh City of Vietnam
after a four-day visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in this largest city of the South Island of New
Zealand, Li visited a sheep farm and met with Richard Johnson,
chairman of Canterbury Regional Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
