<HEADLINE> U.S. not Concerned over Yeltsin Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
today that there was no reason for concern over the health of
Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Both the State Department and the White House denied they are
concerned over the health of Yeltsin, who has been admitted to a
sanitarium with a viral infection.
</P>
<P>
"We have no reason to believe that he's not at the top of his
game, that he's in good health. He has recovered amazingly well from
the surgery he had (last year)," State Department spokesman James
Foley told a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
A White House official traveling with U.S. President Bill
Clinton in New York told reporters who asked about Yeltsin's
health: "Given the information we have, we don't see reason for
concern."
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Kremlin said Yeltsin had an acute
respiratory viral infection resulting from a cold and would stay
at a sanitarium outside Moscow for 10 to 12 days.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who has established a warm relationship with the
Russian leader in a series of summit meetings, was sending a note
wishing him well, White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore also said there appeared to be no need
for "undue concern" about Yeltsin's health.
</P>
<P>
"If what his doctors are saying is accurate, and we believe it
is. this is a temporary matter from which he will quickly
recover," said Gore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
