<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Cyprus Begins in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A two-day conference began here
today to discuss the prospects for Cyprus's accession to the
European Union (EU) and the U.S. initiative on the protracted
Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The conference, entitled "The Cyprus Problem: Prospect of
Solution," which has been organized by the Greek Coalition of the
Left and Progress, is attended by political personalities,
representatives of Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot parties and
academics.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the conference, Nikos Konstantopoulos, president of
the Greek coalition, said that the new developments created new
opportunities to solve the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The year 1998, especially after the island's presidential
elections, would be a critical one for the Cyprus issue, he said,
adding that the Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots should create
conditions for dialogue aiming at finding a solution to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Haralambos Christophorou, Cyprus ambassador to
Greece, said that the Cyprus government wants to cooperate in
seeking a solution to the problem. He urged the Turkish Cypriots
to take the same position.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. initiative was expected to intensify after next
Feburary's presidential elections, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
In June, Richard Holbrooke was appointed U.S. presidential
emissary for Cyprus as part of efforts by Washington to help
settle the problem, but no substantial progress has been made so
far.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern part of the island after a pro-
Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
