<HEADLINE> Syrian President Urges Muslim States Not to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad
today called on Muslim states not to compromise with Israel as it
is forbidden by Islam.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the the Eighth Summit of the Organization of
Islamic Conference, Assad said that Muslim states should halt
their compromises with Israel. Appeasement has only encouraged
more extremism on part of the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
He said "compromise with Israel is forbidden by Islam, because
Israel is a regime which has violated Islam, Muslims and their
sanctities."
</P>
<P>
He said "Israeli aggression against Arabs is an Islamic as
well as Arab problem, therefore we all have to cooperate to
reverse the aggression and to restore Arabs' rights."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the expansionist policies of Israel, Assad said
the Arab-Israeli conflict had been a major detriment to the world
peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
He warned of the threat posed by the Israel's huge arsenal of
weapons supplied by the U.S. and other major powers and said that
"while the Israeli military power is enhanced, the Arabs are under
constant pressure to be void of any means to defend themselves."
</P>
