<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Three-Year EFF Credit for Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved a three-year credit for Panama
equivalent to about 162 million U.S. dollars under the Extended
Fund Facility (EFF).
</P>
<P>
The credit is provided in support of the Panama government's
medium-term economic reform program for 1998-2000.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to deepen and broaden structural reforms
within the context of continued prudent fiscal policy and low
inflation, with the objective of promoting sustainable output and
employment growth and reducing poverty.
</P>
<P>
The program also aims at raising GDP growth to 5 percent by
the year 2000 from 2.5 percent in 1996, while holding inflation at
about 1.5 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
The EFF is an IMF financing facility that supports medium-term
programs that seek to overcome balance of payments difficulties
stemming from macroeconomic imbalances and structural programs.
</P>
<P>
Panama joined the IMF in March 1946. Its quota is about 202
million dollars equivalent and its outstanding use of IMF
financing currently totals about 132 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Dollar Falls Sharply Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar plunged
against the Japanese yen today, and then recovered most of its
losses at the closing.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also fell against the German mark as both currencies
were hurt by the yen's surge during European trading.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell as much as 1.29 yen in overnight trading as
investors grew confident that the Japanese government would act
boldly to shore up the financial system. But sentiment quickly
ebbed once traders arrived at work in New York.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 129.28
Japanese yen, down from 129.59 late Tuesday. The dollar was
changing hands in New York at 1.7862 German marks, down from
1.7904.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday:
1.4460 Swiss francs, down from 1.4528; 5.9800 French francs, down
from 5.9902; 1,748.50 Italian lire, down from 1,751; and 1.4239
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4200.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6504 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6507 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
