<DOCNO> XIE19971211.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Luxembourg, Greek Premiers Hold talks in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Luxembourg Prime
Minister Jean-Claude Juncker today discussed with his Greek
counterpart Costas Simitis the coordination of economic policies
and support for the political independence of the European Central
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks, Juncker, current president of the
EU Council, said that he hoped the 15 member states could reach
agreement on the issue of an informal monetary council.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that Luxembourg could contribute to building a bridge
between the founding members of the Euro currency and those who
are not, which in any case would be able to meet informally.
</P>
<P>
All European countries, he stressed, could become EU members
only if they fulfilled the conditions established in Copenhagen,
particularly those concerning respect for human rights and good
neighborly relations.
</P>
<P>
Juncker said that EU's expansion to include central and eastern
countries and Cyprus was a different issue to EU-Turkey relations.
</P>
<P>
He added that negotiations with all eleven prospective members
should begin at once, but that each country should be dealt with
separately according to its degree of readiness.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said that as many countries as possible should be able
to join the EU, so long as certain rules were observed with regard
to safeguarding European principles.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized that the accession talks between the EU and
Cyprus should begin as scheduled in April next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
