<HEADLINE> Egypt Mourns Terrorism Victims in Luxor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXOR (Egypt), December 10 (Xinhua) -- A memorial service was
held today in Egypt's southern resort Luxor for the victims of the
shocking terrorist attack here last month.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Egyptian Ministry of Culture, the service,
under the theme of conveying a "message from Thebes to the world,"
was intended to express Egypt's sorrow and regret for the victims.
</P>
<P>
Held at the Hatshepsut temple, which witnessed the killing of
58 foreign tourists and four Egyptians on November 17, the service
was attended by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Prime Minister
Kamal El-Ganzouri, several cabinet ministers and a representative
of a U.N. organization in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The service began with the martyr anthem played live by the
side of a torch erected on the site of the incident, followed by
the orchestra and choir singing Verdi's memorial service
masterpiece and Egyptian patriotic songs.
</P>
<P>
Observing a two-minute silence, the lights on the site went dim
until darkness enveloped the whole arena, and every participant
lit a candle solemnly moving towards the torch.
</P>
<P>
The renowned Egyptian novelist and Noble Prize Laureate Naguib
Mahfouz addressed a recorded "message from Thebes to the world,"
which denounced the terrorist act.
</P>
<P>
Ambassadors and cultural attaches of 30 countries, including
those who have lost compatriots in the incident, also participated
in the service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
