<HEADLINE> Lebanese Protest Against Israel's Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Nearly a hundred mothers of
Lebanese prisoners held in Israeli jails today staged a sit-in
protest against human rights abuses by Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The protest was staged in front of the Beirut office of the
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) on the occasion
of the International Human Rights Day.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the demonstrators, Salim Hoss, a current parliament
member, said that the human rights day is the day for the Lebanese
people whose rights are violated by Israeli occupation of their
territory.
</P>
<P>
Israelis infringed on human rights by nearly everyday's attack
on south Lebanon and the western sector of Lebanon's Bekka Valley.
</P>
<P>
Those held in Israeli jails did not commit any crime but are
opposed to Israel's occupation, said Hoss.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Israelis are using all kinds of ways to torture
and ill-treat the prisoners and cut off their contacts with their
families.
</P>
<P>
Israelis did not permit the ICRC staff to inspect the
conditions of prisons and barred their relatives from meeting them
or sending letters to them, he said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed on the international community to pay attention to
the prisoners and seek to release them with the help of the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
Israel holds 125 Lebanese prisoners at Khiam prison in south
Lebanon run by its militia ally South Lebanese Army, while 50
other Lebanese are held in Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
