<HEADLINE> Qatar Likely to Host Next Islamic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A Qatari delegate to the eighth
Islamic summit said here today that his country has been chosen to
host next summit of the Organization of the Islamic Conference
(OIC) in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The official, identified as Ahmad Ali, said all the other
member states of the Islamic body supported Qatar's bid for
hosting the ninth summit and a decision in this regard will be
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Still reeling from last month's Doha economic conference,
which was boycott by a majority of Arab countries, Qatar launched
the bid for the next OIC summit partly as an fence-mending effort
with the Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Qatar had insisted on holding the U.S.-advocated Doha meeting
despite strong opposition from most Arab states, which loathe
sitting with Israel under one roof while the Middle East peace
process was on the brink of collapse due to Israel's hardline
policies.
</P>
<P>
Ali said Qatar's bid was unchallenged. "We have the ability to
host the summit, and the Doha meeting, a world-class conference,
is a proof," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi
said several other countries have also offered to host the next
Islamic summit.
</P>
<P>
No decision on the venue has been made so far, he said, adding
that the OIC leaders will reach a consensus on the issue Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to Arab boycott of the Doha meeting, almost all OIC
members attend the Islamic summit in Tehran, much to the
annoyance of the U.S. which repeatedly accuses Iran of sponsoring
terrorism and has tightened the screws of sanctions against
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
