<HEADLINE> Iran, Islamic Summit Differ on Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran holds different views on
the Middle East peace process with the Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC), an Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"Our policies on the so-called Middle East peace process is
different with that of the OIC," Spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi told
Xinhua correspondents on the sidelines of the OIC summit.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran is opposing the peace process while some
other OIC members hold moderate views on the issue, though all the
OIC members consider Israel as a threat to the Islamic countries.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has announced its opposition to relations between
Islamic countries and Israel, a "usurper of Arab lands" as they
described, proposing those Islamic countries which have recognized
or establish ties with Israel to reconsider their minds.
</P>
<P>
However, the OIC foreign ministers' meeting last week only
adopted a draft resolution on opposition to military cooperation
between Islamic countries and Israel, since many OIC members
supported ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi also noted that there are still some other
differences among the OIC members like that on the issue of
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said that the differences will be discussed in Thursday's
closing debates, and the OIC leaders will try to reach an
agreement on the Tehran Declaration.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi dismissed the claim that the Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel's scheduled leaving the OIC summit Wednesday
evening is in protest against the draft resolution on opposition
to Islamic countries' military cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey is blamed by OIC members for its military
cooperation with Israel, but the criticism is "understandable for
Turkey."
</P>
<P>
Leaders from the 55 OIC members are attending the three-day
summit during which they described Israel as the "Zionist regime,"
and "occupier of Qods (Jerusalem) which is holy to
Muslims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
